{"title_page": "Wanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof", "text_new": "{{Infobox station\n| symbol              = rail\n| symbol2             = s-bahn\n| symbol_location     = de \n| symbol_location2    = rhine-ruhr\n| image               = Wanne Eickel Hauptbahnhof01.jpg\n| name                = Wanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof\n| caption             = The station building\n| type                = Through station\n| platforms           = 8\n| trains              =\n| code                = {{Deutsche Bahn station codes|code=6533<ref name =categories/>|ds100= EWAN<ref name=Eisenbahnatlas >{{cite book| title=Eisenbahnatlas Deutschland| trans-title=German railway atlas| language=de| edition=2009/2010 |publisher=Schweers + Wall | year=2009 |isbn=978-3-89494-139-0}}</ref>{{page needed|date=April 2020}}|ibnr=8000192|category=3<ref name=categories>{{DBCatsURL}}</ref>}}\n| opened              =* 1856 (freight yard)\n* 1864 (passenger station)\n| architect           =\n| address             = Heinz-R\u00fchmann-Platz 1, [[Herne, Germany|Herne]], [[North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n| country             = Germany\n| coordinates         = {{coord|51|31|53|N|7|9|57|E|region:DE-NW_type:railwaystation|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation           = <!-- {{convert|0|m|abbr=on}} -->\n| owned               = [[Deutsche Bahn]]\n| operator            = {{Plainlist|1=\n*[[DB Netz]]\n*[[DB Station&Service]]\n}}\n| line                =\n* [[Wanne-Eickel\u2013Hamburg railway|Wanne-Eickel\u2013Hamburg]]\n* [[Duisburg\u2013Dortmund railway|Dortmund\u2013Duisburg]] \n* [[Duisburg-Ruhrort\u2013Dortmund railway|Duisburg-Ruhrort\u2013Dortmund]]\n* [[Bochum\u2013Gelsenkirchen railway|Bochum\u2013Gelsenkirchen]]\n| train_operators     = [[Abellio Rail NRW]]<br>[[DB Regio NRW]]<br>[[eurobahn]]<br>[[NordWestBahn]]\n| connections         = {{S-Bahn-NRW|2}}\n| zone                = [[Verkehrsverbund Rhein-Ruhr|VRR]]: 272<ref>{{cite web |title=Liniennetzplan/Wabenplan |url=https://www.bogestra.de/fileadmin/dam/pdf/Sonstiges/Linienplaene/Wabenplan_2013.pdf |publisher=[[BOGESTRA|Bochum-Gelsenkirchener Stra\u00dfenbahnen AG]] |accessdate=31 October 2019 |date=April 2013}}</ref>\n| website             = [https://www.bahnhof.de/bahnhof-de/Wanne-Eickel_Hbf.html www.bahnhof.de]\n| map_type            = North Rhine-Westphalia#Germany#Europe\n| map_caption         = Location in North Rhine-Westphalia##Location in Germany##Location in Europe\n| map_dot_label       = Wanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof\n| embedded            = {{Infobox mapframe\n| stroke-colour       = #C60C30\n| stroke-width        = 3\n| marker              = rail-underground\n| marker-colour       = #009D58\n| zoom                = 15\n}}\n| services            = \n{{s-rail|title=DB Fernverkehr}}\n{{s-line|system=DB-ICE|line=47|previous=Gelsenkirchen|next=Recklinghausen|type=South|type2=M\u00fcnster|notemid=ICE 914/915 only}}\n{{s-line|system=DB-IC|line=32|previous=Gelsenkirchen|next=Recklinghausen|type=Klagenfurt|type2=M\u00fcnster|notemid=EC 115 only}}\n{{s-line|system=DB-IC|line=35|previous=Gelsenkirchen|next=Recklinghausen|type=South|type2=North}}\n{{s-rail|title=Abellio Rail NRW}}\n{{s-line|system=RB-NRW|line=32|previous=Gelsenkirchen|next=Herne}}\n{{s-line|system=RB-NRW|line=46|previous=Gelsenkirchen|next=Bochum-Riemke}}\n{{s-rail|title=DB Regio NRW}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-NRW|line=2|previous=Gelsenkirchen|next=Recklinghausen}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-NRW|line=42|previous=Gelsenkirchen|next=Recklinghausen S\u00fcd}}\n{{s-rail|title=eurobahn}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-NRW|line=3|previous=Essen-Altenessen|next=Herne|}}\n{{s-rail|title=NordWestBahn}}\n{{s-line|system=RB-NRW|line=43|previous=Gelsenkirchen-Zoo|next=Herne}}\n{{s-rail|title=RRSB}}\n{{s-line|system=RRSB|line=S2|previous=Gelsenkirchen|next=Herne|type=Essen|}}\n| other_services      = \n{{s-rail|title=Bochum Stadtbahn}}\n{{s-line|system=VRR|line=306|previous=|next=Am Buschmannshof}}\n}}\n\n'''Wanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof''' is a railway station in the former city of Wanne-Eickel, now part of [[Herne, Germany|Herne]] in western [[Germany]].\n\n==History ==\nThe station grew out of the ''Pluto-Thies'' freight yard, opened in 1856 on the [[Duisburg\u2013Dortmund Railway|Duisburg\u2013Dortmund line]] section of the [[Cologne-Minden Railway Company]]'s trunk line, which was opened in 1847. In 1864, a halt was opened there for passengers. In 1867 a new freight yard was opened, which was initially called ''Pluto'', but changed to ''Wanne'' (literally \u201cbasin\u201d, a description of the landscape) in 1869, because the surrounding villages could not agree on a name for the yard. The station's name was reflected in 1875 when the villages of Eickel, Bicker, Crange, Holsterhausen and R\u00f6hlinghausen were merged under the name of Amt Wanne.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nrwbahnarchiv.bplaced.net/esn/EWAN.htm| title=Wanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof (EWAN) operations| work=NRW rail archive| publisher=Andr\u00e9 Joost| language=German| accessdate=17 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nWith the opening of the [[Wanne-Eickel\u2013Hamburg railway|line to M\u00fcnster]] on 1 January 1870, Wanne station became a railway junction. In 1913 the station building and the track work were rebuilt and extended.\n\nAfter the formation of the city of Wanne-Eickel in 1926, the station was renamed ''Wanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof''. It became the largest marshalling yard in the central Ruhr area and the only station in the Ruhr that included all four forms of rail operations: in addition to its role as a marshalling yard, it was the home depot for over 300 locomotives along with associated rolling stock, a freight yard and a passenger station.\n\n==Current operations==\nWanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof is a station of major traffic importance as a crossroads on the east-west Dortmund\u2013Duisburg line and the north-south M\u00fcnster\u2013Essen line, which among other things, is the beginning of the [[Wanne-Eickel\u2013Hamburg railway|Rollbahn]] (rolling railway) to [[Hamburg]]. In addition, the station is located on the [[Duisburg-Ruhrort\u2013Dortmund railway|Emscher Valley Railway]] (Dortmund\u2013Wanne-Eickel\u2013Dorsten) and the Bochum\u2013Gelsenkirchen Railway (also known as the ''Gl\u00fcckauf-Bahn''\u2014 a reference to [[Gl\u00fcck auf]], the traditional German miners greeting). Part of the old marshalling yard still operates with shunting from west to east over a hump, but other freight operations are closed.\n\nFollowing the merger of the cities of Herne and Wanne-Eickel in 1975 the name of the station remained as Wanne\u2013Eickel Hauptbahnhof, although it is the largest station in the city of Herne on its current boundaries. In 2003, [[Deutsche Bahn]] planned to rename it ''Herne-Wanne'' or ''Herne Hauptbahnhof''. However, these plans met with considerable resistance in the Wanne area, as well as from local politicians in Herne.\n\n==Lines==\n===Long-distance===\nWanne-Eickel is served by one [[Intercity (Deutsche Bahn)|InterCity]] service:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Line !! Route !! Frequency\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|ICE|47|ICE}}\n| [[M\u00fcnster Hauptbahnhof|M\u00fcnster]] \u2013 [[Recklinghausen Hauptbahnhof|Recklinghausen]] \u2013 '''Wanne-Eickel''' \u2013 [[Gelsenkirchen Hauptbahnhof|Gelsenkirchen]] \u2013 [[Essen Hauptbahnhof|Essen]] \u2013 [[K\u00f6ln Messe/Deutz|K\u00f6ln]] \u2013 [[Frankfurt Airport long-distance station|Frankfurt Airport]] \u2013 [[Mannheim Hauptbahnhof|Mannheim]] \u2013 [[Stuttgart Hauptbahnhof|Stuttgart]]\n| One a day\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|IC|35|IC}}\n| [[Norddeich Mole railway station|Norddeich Mole]] \u2013 [[Leer (Ostfriesland) station|Leer (Ostfriesl)]] \u2013 [[M\u00fcnster (Westfalen) Hauptbahnhof|M\u00fcnster (Westf)]] \u2013 Recklinghausen \u2013 '''Wanne-Eickel''' \u2013 [[Gelsenkirchen Hauptbahnhof|Gelsenkirchen]] \u2013 [[Oberhausen Hauptbahnhof|Oberhausen]] \u2013 [[Duisburg Hauptbahnhof|Duisburg]] \u2013 [[D\u00fcsseldorf Hauptbahnhof|D\u00fcsseldorf]] \u2013 [[K\u00f6ln Hauptbahnhof|Cologne]] (\u2013 [[Bonn Hauptbahnhof|Bonn]] \u2013 [[Koblenz Hauptbahnhof|Koblenz]])\n| Every 2 hours\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|EC|115}}\n| M\u00fcnster (Westf) \u2013 Recklinghausen \u2013 '''Wanne-Eickel''' \u2013 Oberhausen \u2013 D\u00fcsseldorf \u2013 K\u00f6ln \u2013 Mainz \u2013 Mannheim \u2013 Stuttgart \u2013 [[Augsburg Hauptbahnhof|Augsburg]] \u2013 [[M\u00fcnchen Hauptbahnhof|Munich]] \u2013 [[Prien am Chiemsee station|Prien am Chiemsee]] \u2013 [[Freilassing station|Freilassing]] \u2013 [[Salzburg Hauptbahnhof|Salzburg]] \u2013 [[Klagenfurt Hauptbahnhof|Klagenfurt]]\n| One a day\n|}\n===Regional===\n\nWanne-Eickel is served by the two [[Regional-Express]] and three [[Regionalbahn]] lines, as well as the [[Rhine-Ruhr S-Bahn]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|- class=\"hintergrundfarbe5\"\n! Line !! Line name !! Route\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|2}}\n| [[Rhein-Haard-Express]]\n| [[M\u00f6nchengladbach Hauptbahnhof|M\u00f6nchengladbach]] \u2013 [[Krefeld Hauptbahnhof|Krefeld]] \u2013 [[Duisburg Hauptbahnhof|Duisburg]] \u2013 [[Essen Hauptbahnhof|Essen]] \u2013 '''Wanne-Eickel''' \u2013 [[Gelsenkirchen Hauptbahnhof|Gelsenkirchen]] \u2013 [[Recklinghausen Hauptbahnhof|Recklinghausen]] \u2013 [[M\u00fcnster Hauptbahnhof|M\u00fcnster (Westf)]]\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|3}}\n| [[Rhein-Emscher-Express]]\n| [[D\u00fcsseldorf Hauptbahnhof|D\u00fcsseldorf]] \u2013 Duisburg \u2013 [[Oberhausen Hauptbahnhof|Oberhausen]] \u2013 '''Wanne-Eickel''' \u2013 Gelsenkirchen \u2013 [[Herne station|Herne]] \u2013 [[Dortmund Hauptbahnhof|Dortmund]] \u2013 [[Minden (Westfalen) station|Hamm (Westf)]]\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|42}}\n| [[Niers-Haard-Express]]\n| [[M\u00f6nchengladbach Hauptbahnhof|M\u00f6nchengladbach]] \u2013 [[Krefeld Hauptbahnhof|Krefeld]] \u2013 Essen \u2013 '''Wanne-Eickel''' \u2013 Gelsenkirchen \u2013 Recklinghausen \u2013 Haltern \u2013 M\u00fcnster (Westf)\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RB|32}}\n| [[Rhein-Emscher-Bahn]]\n| Duisburg \u2013 [[Essen-Altenessen station|Essen-Altenessen]] \u2013 Gelsenkirchen \u2013 '''Wanne-Eickel''' \u2013 [[Castrop-Rauxel Hauptbahnhof|Castrop-Rauxel]] \u2013  Dortmund \n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RB|43}}\n| [[Emschertal-Bahn]]\n| [[Dorsten station|Dorsten]] \u2013 '''Wanne-Eickel''' \u2013 Herne \u2013 Dortmund\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RB|46}}\n| [[Gl\u00fcckauf-Bahn]]\n| Gelsenkirchen  \u2013 '''Wanne-Eickel''' \u2013 [[Bochum Hauptbahnhof|Bochum]]\n|-\n| {{S-Bahn-NRW|2}}\n| [[Rhine-Ruhr S-Bahn]]\n| Essen \u2013 Gelsenkirchen \u2013 '''Wanne-Eickel''' \u2013 Herne \u2013 Dortmund\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{cite web |url=http://nrwbahnarchiv.bplaced.net/bf/8000192.htm | title=Wanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof | work=NRW rail archive |publisher= Andr\u00e9 Joost |language=German | accessdate= 17 September 2011}}\n*{{cite web| url= http://www.deutschebahn.com/site/bahn/de/geschaefte/infrastruktur__schiene/netz/netzzugang/dokumente/Bahnhof/SNB/E/EWAN__NBS.pdf  | title= Wanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof track plan |publisher =[[Deutsche Bahn]] |format= PDF |accessdate=17 September 2011 |language=German}}\n\n{{Commons category|Wanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:S2 (Rhine-Ruhr S-Bahn)]]\n[[Category:Rhine-Ruhr S-Bahn stations]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Herne, North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1864]]\n[[Category:1864 establishments in Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox station\n| symbol              = rail\n| symbol2             = s-bahn\n| symbol_location     = de \n| symbol_location2    = rhine-ruhr\n| image               = Wanne Eickel Hauptbahnhof01.jpg\n| name                = Wanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof\n| caption             = The station building\n| type                = Through station\n| platforms           = 8\n| trains              =\n| code                = {{Deutsche Bahn station codes|code=6533<ref name =categories/>|ds100= EWAN<ref name=Eisenbahnatlas >{{cite book|title=Eisenbahnatlas Deutschland (German railway atlas)| edition=2009/2010 |publisher= Schweers + Wall | year= 2009 |isbn= 978-3-89494-139-0}}</ref>|ibnr=8000192|category=3<ref name =categories >{{DBCatsURL}}</ref>}}\n| opened              =* 1856 (freight yard)\n* 1864 (passenger station)\n| architect           =\n| address             = Heinz-R\u00fchmann-Platz 1, [[Herne, Germany|Herne]], [[North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n| country             = Germany\n| coordinates         = {{coord|51|31|53|N|7|9|57|E|region:DE-NW_type:railwaystation|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation           = <!-- {{convert|0|m|abbr=on}} -->\n| owned               = [[Deutsche Bahn]]\n| operator            = {{Plainlist|1=\n*[[DB Netz]]\n*[[DB Station&Service]]\n}}\n| line                =\n* [[Wanne-Eickel\u2013Hamburg railway|Wanne-Eickel\u2013Hamburg]]\n* [[Duisburg\u2013Dortmund railway|Dortmund\u2013Duisburg]] \n* [[Duisburg-Ruhrort\u2013Dortmund railway|Duisburg-Ruhrort\u2013Dortmund]]\n* [[Bochum\u2013Gelsenkirchen railway|Bochum\u2013Gelsenkirchen]]\n| train_operators     = [[Abellio Rail NRW]]<br>[[DB Regio NRW]]<br>[[eurobahn]]<br>[[NordWestBahn]]\n| connections         = {{S-Bahn-NRW|2}}\n| zone                = [[Verkehrsverbund Rhein-Ruhr|VRR]]: 272<ref>{{cite web |title=Liniennetzplan/Wabenplan |url=https://www.bogestra.de/fileadmin/dam/pdf/Sonstiges/Linienplaene/Wabenplan_2013.pdf |publisher=[[BOGESTRA|Bochum-Gelsenkirchener Stra\u00dfenbahnen AG]] |accessdate=31 October 2019 |date=April 2013}}</ref>\n| website             = [https://www.bahnhof.de/bahnhof-de/Wanne-Eickel_Hbf.html www.bahnhof.de]\n| map_type            = North Rhine-Westphalia#Germany#Europe\n| map_caption         = Location in North Rhine-Westphalia##Location in Germany##Location in Europe\n| map_dot_label       = Wanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof\n| embedded            = {{Infobox mapframe\n| stroke-colour       = #C60C30\n| stroke-width        = 3\n| marker              = rail-underground\n| marker-colour       = #009D58\n| zoom                = 15\n}}\n| services            = \n{{s-rail|title=DB Fernverkehr}}\n{{s-line|system=DB-ICE|line=47|previous=Gelsenkirchen|next=Recklinghausen|type=South|type2=M\u00fcnster|notemid=ICE 914/915 only}}\n{{s-line|system=DB-IC|line=32|previous=Gelsenkirchen|next=Recklinghausen|type=Klagenfurt|type2=M\u00fcnster|notemid=EC 115 only}}\n{{s-line|system=DB-IC|line=35|previous=Gelsenkirchen|next=Recklinghausen|type=South|type2=North}}\n{{s-rail|title=Abellio Rail NRW}}\n{{s-line|system=RB-NRW|line=32|previous=Gelsenkirchen|next=Herne}}\n{{s-line|system=RB-NRW|line=46|previous=Gelsenkirchen|next=Bochum-Riemke}}\n{{s-rail|title=DB Regio NRW}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-NRW|line=2|previous=Gelsenkirchen|next=Recklinghausen}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-NRW|line=42|previous=Gelsenkirchen|next=Recklinghausen S\u00fcd}}\n{{s-rail|title=eurobahn}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-NRW|line=3|previous=Essen-Altenessen|next=Herne|}}\n{{s-rail|title=NordWestBahn}}\n{{s-line|system=RB-NRW|line=43|previous=Gelsenkirchen-Zoo|next=Herne}}\n{{s-rail|title=RRSB}}\n{{s-line|system=RRSB|line=S2|previous=Gelsenkirchen|next=Herne|type=Essen|}}\n| other_services      = \n{{s-rail|title=Bochum Stadtbahn}}\n{{s-line|system=VRR|line=306|previous=|next=Am Buschmannshof}}\n}}\n\n'''Wanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof''' is a railway station in the former city of Wanne-Eickel, now part of [[Herne, Germany|Herne]] in western [[Germany]].\n\n==History ==\nThe station grew out of the ''Pluto-Thies'' freight yard, opened in 1856 on the [[Duisburg\u2013Dortmund Railway|Duisburg\u2013Dortmund line]] section of the [[Cologne-Minden Railway Company]]'s trunk line, which was opened in 1847. In 1864, a halt was opened there for passengers. In 1867 a new freight yard was opened, which was initially called ''Pluto'', but changed to ''Wanne'' (literally \u201cbasin\u201d, a description of the landscape) in 1869, because the surrounding villages could not agree on a name for the yard. The station's name was reflected in 1875 when the villages of Eickel, Bicker, Crange, Holsterhausen and R\u00f6hlinghausen were merged under the name of Amt Wanne.<ref>\n {{cite web |url=http://nrwbahnarchiv.bplaced.net/esn/EWAN.htm | title=Wanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof (EWAN) operations | work=NRW rail archive |publisher= Andr\u00e9 Joost |language=German | accessdate= 17 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nWith the opening of the [[Wanne-Eickel\u2013Hamburg railway|line to M\u00fcnster]] on 1 January 1870, Wanne station became a railway junction. In 1913 the station building and the track work were rebuilt and extended.\n\nAfter the formation of the city of Wanne-Eickel in 1926, the station was renamed ''Wanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof''. It became the largest marshalling yard in the central Ruhr area and the only station in the Ruhr that included all four forms of rail operations: in addition to its role as a marshalling yard, it was the home depot for over 300 locomotives along with associated rolling stock, a freight yard and a passenger station.\n\n==Current operations==\nWanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof is a station of major traffic importance as a crossroads on the east-west Dortmund\u2013Duisburg line and the north-south M\u00fcnster\u2013Essen line, which among other things, is the beginning of the [[Wanne-Eickel\u2013Hamburg railway|Rollbahn]] (rolling railway) to [[Hamburg]]. In addition, the station is located on the [[Duisburg-Ruhrort\u2013Dortmund railway|Emscher Valley Railway]] (Dortmund\u2013Wanne-Eickel\u2013Dorsten) and the Bochum\u2013Gelsenkirchen Railway (also known as the ''Gl\u00fcckauf-Bahn''\u2014 a reference to [[Gl\u00fcck auf]], the traditional German miners greeting). Part of the old marshalling yard still operates with shunting from west to east over a hump, but other freight operations are closed.\n\nFollowing the merger of the cities of Herne and Wanne-Eickel in 1975 the name of the station remained as Wanne\u2013Eickel Hauptbahnhof, although it is the largest station in the city of Herne on its current boundaries. In 2003, [[Deutsche Bahn]] planned to rename it ''Herne-Wanne'' or ''Herne Hauptbahnhof''. However, these plans met with considerable resistance in the Wanne area, as well as from local politicians in Herne.\n\n==Lines==\n===Long-distance===\nWanne-Eickel is served by one [[Intercity (Deutsche Bahn)|InterCity]] service:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Line !! Route !! Frequency\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|ICE|47|ICE}}\n| [[M\u00fcnster Hauptbahnhof|M\u00fcnster]] \u2013 [[Recklinghausen Hauptbahnhof|Recklinghausen]] \u2013 '''Wanne-Eickel''' \u2013 [[Gelsenkirchen Hauptbahnhof|Gelsenkirchen]] \u2013 [[Essen Hauptbahnhof|Essen]] \u2013 [[K\u00f6ln Messe/Deutz|K\u00f6ln]] \u2013 [[Frankfurt Airport long-distance station|Frankfurt Airport]] \u2013 [[Mannheim Hauptbahnhof|Mannheim]] \u2013 [[Stuttgart Hauptbahnhof|Stuttgart]]\n| One a day\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|IC|35|IC}}\n| [[Norddeich Mole railway station|Norddeich Mole]] \u2013 [[Leer (Ostfriesland) station|Leer (Ostfriesl)]] \u2013 [[M\u00fcnster (Westfalen) Hauptbahnhof|M\u00fcnster (Westf)]] \u2013 Recklinghausen \u2013 '''Wanne-Eickel''' \u2013 [[Gelsenkirchen Hauptbahnhof|Gelsenkirchen]] \u2013 [[Oberhausen Hauptbahnhof|Oberhausen]] \u2013 [[Duisburg Hauptbahnhof|Duisburg]] \u2013 [[D\u00fcsseldorf Hauptbahnhof|D\u00fcsseldorf]] \u2013 [[K\u00f6ln Hauptbahnhof|Cologne]] (\u2013 [[Bonn Hauptbahnhof|Bonn]] \u2013 [[Koblenz Hauptbahnhof|Koblenz]])\n| Every 2 hours\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|EC|115}}\n| M\u00fcnster (Westf) \u2013 Recklinghausen \u2013 '''Wanne-Eickel''' \u2013 Oberhausen \u2013 D\u00fcsseldorf \u2013 K\u00f6ln \u2013 Mainz \u2013 Mannheim \u2013 Stuttgart \u2013 [[Augsburg Hauptbahnhof|Augsburg]] \u2013 [[M\u00fcnchen Hauptbahnhof|Munich]] \u2013 [[Prien am Chiemsee station|Prien am Chiemsee]] \u2013 [[Freilassing station|Freilassing]] \u2013 [[Salzburg Hauptbahnhof|Salzburg]] \u2013 [[Klagenfurt Hauptbahnhof|Klagenfurt]]\n| One a day\n|}\n===Regional===\n\nWanne-Eickel is served by the two [[Regional-Express]] and three [[Regionalbahn]] lines, as well as the [[Rhine-Ruhr S-Bahn]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|- class=\"hintergrundfarbe5\"\n! Line !! Line name !! Route\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|2}}\n| [[Rhein-Haard-Express]]\n| [[M\u00f6nchengladbach Hauptbahnhof|M\u00f6nchengladbach]] \u2013 [[Krefeld Hauptbahnhof|Krefeld]] \u2013 [[Duisburg Hauptbahnhof|Duisburg]] \u2013 [[Essen Hauptbahnhof|Essen]] \u2013 '''Wanne-Eickel''' \u2013 [[Gelsenkirchen Hauptbahnhof|Gelsenkirchen]] \u2013 [[Recklinghausen Hauptbahnhof|Recklinghausen]] \u2013 [[M\u00fcnster Hauptbahnhof|M\u00fcnster (Westf)]]\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|3}}\n| [[Rhein-Emscher-Express]]\n| [[D\u00fcsseldorf Hauptbahnhof|D\u00fcsseldorf]] \u2013 Duisburg \u2013 [[Oberhausen Hauptbahnhof|Oberhausen]] \u2013 '''Wanne-Eickel''' \u2013 Gelsenkirchen \u2013 [[Herne station|Herne]] \u2013 [[Dortmund Hauptbahnhof|Dortmund]] \u2013 [[Minden (Westfalen) station|Hamm (Westf)]]\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|42}}\n| [[Niers-Haard-Express]]\n| [[M\u00f6nchengladbach Hauptbahnhof|M\u00f6nchengladbach]] \u2013 [[Krefeld Hauptbahnhof|Krefeld]] \u2013 Essen \u2013 '''Wanne-Eickel''' \u2013 Gelsenkirchen \u2013 Recklinghausen \u2013 Haltern \u2013 M\u00fcnster (Westf)\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RB|32}}\n| [[Rhein-Emscher-Bahn]]\n| Duisburg \u2013 [[Essen-Altenessen station|Essen-Altenessen]] \u2013 Gelsenkirchen \u2013 '''Wanne-Eickel''' \u2013 [[Castrop-Rauxel Hauptbahnhof|Castrop-Rauxel]] \u2013  Dortmund \n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RB|43}}\n| [[Emschertal-Bahn]]\n| [[Dorsten station|Dorsten]] \u2013 '''Wanne-Eickel''' \u2013 Herne \u2013 Dortmund\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RB|46}}\n| [[Gl\u00fcckauf-Bahn]]\n| Gelsenkirchen  \u2013 '''Wanne-Eickel''' \u2013 [[Bochum Hauptbahnhof|Bochum]]\n|-\n| {{S-Bahn-NRW|2}}\n| [[Rhine-Ruhr S-Bahn]]\n| Essen \u2013 Gelsenkirchen \u2013 '''Wanne-Eickel''' \u2013 Herne \u2013 Dortmund\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{cite web |url=http://nrwbahnarchiv.bplaced.net/bf/8000192.htm | title=Wanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof | work=NRW rail archive |publisher= Andr\u00e9 Joost |language=German | accessdate= 17 September 2011}}\n*{{cite web| url= http://www.deutschebahn.com/site/bahn/de/geschaefte/infrastruktur__schiene/netz/netzzugang/dokumente/Bahnhof/SNB/E/EWAN__NBS.pdf  | title= Wanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof track plan |publisher =[[Deutsche Bahn]] |format= PDF |accessdate=17 September 2011 |language=German}}\n\n{{Commons category|Wanne-Eickel Hauptbahnhof}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:S2 (Rhine-Ruhr S-Bahn)]]\n[[Category:Rhine-Ruhr S-Bahn stations]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Herne, North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1864]]\n[[Category:1864 establishments in Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Slambo", "label": "safe", "comment": "adjust citation detail; mark citation problem", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wanne-Eickel_Hauptbahnhof"}
{"title_page": "Galactic tide", "text_new": "{{short description|Tidal force experienced by objects subject to the gravitational field of a galaxy}}\n[[Image:NGC4676.jpg|thumb|300 px|The [[Mice Galaxies]] NGC 4676]]\n\nA '''galactic tide''' is a [[tidal force]] experienced by objects subject to the [[gravitational field]] of a [[galaxy]] such as the [[Milky Way]]. Particular areas of interest concerning galactic tides include [[Interacting galaxy|galactic collisions]], the disruption of [[dwarf galaxy|dwarf]] or [[satellite galaxy|satellite galaxies]], and the Milky Way's tidal effect on the [[Oort cloud]] of the [[Solar System]].\n\n==Effects on external galaxies==\n{{main|Interacting galaxy}}\n\n=== Galaxy collisions ===\n[[File:NGC40384039 large.jpg|thumb|200 px|The lengthy tidal tails of the colliding [[antennae galaxies]]]] \nTidal forces are dependent on the gradient of a gravitational field, rather than its strength, and so tidal effects are usually limited to the immediate surroundings of a galaxy. Two large galaxies undergoing collisions or passing nearby each other will be subjected to very large tidal forces, often producing the most visually striking demonstrations of galactic tides in action.\n\nTwo interacting galaxies will rarely (if ever) collide head-on, and the tidal forces will distort each galaxy along an axis pointing roughly towards and away from its perturber.  As the two galaxies briefly orbit each other, these distorted regions, which are pulled away from the main body of each galaxy, will be sheared by the galaxy's [[differential rotation]] and flung off into [[intergalactic space]], forming '''tidal tails'''. Such tails are typically strongly curved. If a tail appears to be straight, it is probably being viewed edge-on. The stars and gas that comprise the tails will have been pulled from the easily distorted galactic discs (or other extremities) of one or both bodies, rather than the gravitationally bound galactic centres.<ref name=\"toomre72\">{{cite journal|title=Galactic Bridges and Tails|author1=Toomre A. |author2=Toomre J. |journal=The Astrophysical Journal|volume=178|pages=623\u2013666|date=1972|bibcode=1972ApJ...178..623T|doi=10.1086/151823 }}</ref> Two very prominent examples of collisions producing tidal tails are the [[Mice Galaxies]] and the [[Antennae Galaxies]].\n\nJust as the Moon raises two water tides on opposite sides of the Earth, so a galactic tide produces two arms in its galactic companion. While a large tail is formed if the perturbed galaxy is equal to or less massive than its partner, if it is significantly more massive than the perturbing galaxy, then the trailing arm will be relatively minor, and the leading arm, sometimes called a '''bridge''', will be more prominent.<ref name=\"toomre72\"/> Tidal bridges are typically harder to distinguish than tidal tails: in the first instance, the bridge may be absorbed by the passing galaxy or the resulting merged galaxy, making it visible for a shorter duration than a typical large tail. Secondly, if one of the two galaxies is in the foreground, then the second galaxy \u2014 and the bridge between them \u2014 may be partially obscured. Together, these effects can make it hard to see where one galaxy ends and the next begins. '''Tidal loops''', where a tail joins with its parent galaxy at both ends, are rarer still.<ref>{{cite journal|title=NGC 3310 and its tidal debris: remnants of galaxy evolution|author=Wehner E.H.|display-authors=etal|journal=[[Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society]]|volume=371|issue=3|pages=1047\u20131056|date=2006|bibcode=2006MNRAS.371.1047W|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2966.2006.10757.x |arxiv = astro-ph/0607088 }}</ref>\n\n=== Satellite interactions ===\n[[Image:M31bobo.jpg|thumb|left|300 px|The [[Andromeda Galaxy]]. Note its satellite galaxy [[Messier 32|M32]] at the top left, just above the edge of Andromeda's disk, whose outer arms have been stripped away by Andromeda's tidal forces.]]\nBecause tidal effects are strongest in the immediate vicinity of a galaxy, satellite galaxies are particularly likely to be affected. Such an external force upon a satellite can produce ordered motions within it, leading to large-scale observable effects: the interior structure and motions of a dwarf satellite galaxy may be severely affected by a galactic tide, inducing rotation (as with the tides of the Earth's oceans) or an anomalous mass-to-[[Luminosity#In astronomy|luminosity]] ratio.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Can Galactic Tides Inflate the Apparent M/L's of Dwarf Galaxies?|author1=Piatek S. |author2=Pryor C. |journal=Bulletin of the American Astronomical Society|volume=25|pages=1383|date=1993|bibcode=1993AAS...183.5701P}}</ref> Satellite galaxies can also be subjected to the same tidal stripping that occurs in galactic collisions, where stars and gas are torn from the extremities of a galaxy, possibly to be absorbed by its companion. The dwarf galaxy [[Messier 32|M32]], a satellite galaxy of [[Andromeda Galaxy|Andromeda]], may have lost its [[spiral arm]]s to tidal stripping, while a high star formation rate in the remaining core may be the result of tidally-induced motions of the remaining [[molecular cloud]]s<ref name=\"Bekkietal2001\">{{cite journal\n  | author1=Bekki, Kenji\n  | author2=Couch, Warrick J.\n  | author3=Drinkwater, Michael J.\n  | author4=Gregg, Michael D.\n  | authorlink2=Warrick Couch\n  | title=A New Formation Model for M32: A Threshed Early-Type Spiral Galaxy?\n  | journal=The Astrophysical Journal\n  | date=2001\n  | volume=557\n  | issue=1\n  | pages=Issue 1, pp. L39\u2013L42\n  | bibcode=2001ApJ...557L..39B\n  | doi=10.1086/323075 |arxiv = astro-ph/0107117 | url=http://espace.library.uq.edu.au/view/UQ:37514/UQ37514_OA.pdf\n  }}</ref> (Because tidal forces can knead and compress the interstellar gas clouds inside galaxies, they induce large amounts of [[star formation]] in small satellites.)\n\nThe stripping mechanism is the same as between two comparable galaxies, although its comparatively weak gravitational field ensures that only the satellite, not the host galaxy, is affected. If the satellite is very small compared to the host, the tidal debris tails produced are likely to be symmetric, and follow a very similar orbit, effectively tracing the satellite's path.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Johnston, K.V. |author2=Hernquist, L. |author3=Bolte, M. |title=Fossil Signatures of Ancient Accretion Events in the Halo|journal=The Astrophysical Journal|date=1996|volume=465|pages=278|bibcode=1996ApJ...465..278J|doi=10.1086/177418 |arxiv = astro-ph/9602060 }}</ref> However, if the satellite is reasonably large\u2014typically over one ten thousandth the mass of its host\u2014then the satellite's own gravity may affect the tails, breaking the symmetry and accelerating the tails in different directions. The resulting structure is dependent on both the mass and orbit of the satellite, and the mass and structure of the conjectured [[Dark matter halo|galactic halo]] around the host, and may provide a means of probing the [[dark matter]] [[Potential energy#Gravitational potential|potential]] of a galaxy such as the Milky Way.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Choi, J.-H. |author2=Weinberg, M.D. |author3=Katz, N. |title=The dynamics of tidal tails from massive satellites |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2966.2007.12313.x |date=2007 |journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society |volume=381 |issue=3 |pages=987\u20131000 |arxiv=astro-ph/0702353|bibcode = 2007MNRAS.381..987C }}</ref>\n\nOver many orbits of its parent galaxy, or if the orbit passes too close to it, a dwarf satellite may eventually be completely disrupted, to form a tidal stream of stars and gas wrapping around the larger body. It has been suggested that the extended discs of gas and stars around some galaxies, such as Andromeda, may be the result of the complete tidal disruption (and subsequent merger with the parent galaxy) of a dwarf satellite galaxy.<ref>{{cite journal| title=On the Formation of Extended Galactic Disks by Tidally Disrupted Dwarf Galaxies|author1=Pe\u00f1arrubia J. |author2=McConnachie A. |author3=Babul A. | journal=The Astrophysical Journal| volume=650|issue=1|pages=L33\u2013L36|date=2006|bibcode=2006ApJ...650L..33P| doi=10.1086/508656|arxiv = astro-ph/0606101 }}</ref>\n\n==Effects on bodies within a galaxy==\n{{See also|Oort cloud#Tidal effects}}\n{{refimprove section|date=April 2015}}\nTidal effects are also present within a galaxy, where their gradients are likely to be steepest. This can have consequences for the formation of [[star]]s and [[planetary system]]s. Typically a star's gravity will dominate within its own system, with only the passage of other stars substantially affecting dynamics. However, at the outer reaches of the system, the star's gravity is weak and galactic tides may be significant. In the Solar System, the hypothetical [[Oort cloud]], believed to be the source of long-period [[comet]]s, lies in this transitional region.\n\n[[Image:Kuiper oort-en.svg|thumb|upright=1.3|Diagram of the [[Oort cloud]].]]\n\nThe Oort cloud is believed to be a vast shell surrounding the Solar System, possibly over a [[light-year]] in radius. Across such a vast distance, the gradient of the Milky Way's gravitational field plays a far more noticeable role. Because of this gradient, galactic tides may then deform an otherwise spherical Oort cloud, stretching the cloud in the direction of the galactic centre and compressing it along the other two axes, just as the Earth distends in response to the gravity of the Moon.\n\nThe Sun's gravity is sufficiently weak at such a distance that these small galactic perturbations may be enough to dislodge some [[planetesimals]] from such distant orbits, sending them towards the Sun and planets by significantly reducing their [[perihelia]].<ref>{{cite journal| title=Long-term effects of the Galactic tide on cometary dynamics| author=Fouchard M.| display-authors=etal| journal=Celestial Mechanics and Dynamical Astronomy| volume=95| issue=1\u20134|pages=299\u2013326|date=2006|bibcode=2006CeMDA..95..299F| doi=10.1007/s10569-006-9027-8}}</ref> Such a body, being composed of a rock and ice mixture, would become a comet when subjected to the increased solar radiation present in the inner Solar System.\n\nIt has been suggested that the galactic tide may also contribute to the formation of an Oort cloud, by increasing the perihelia of planetesimals with large [[Apsis|aphelia]].<ref>{{cite journal| title=Orbital Evolution of Planetesimals by the Galactic Tide|author1=Higuchi A., Kokubo E.  |author2=Mukai, T.| journal=Bulletin of the American Astronomical Society| volume=37|pages=521|date=2005|bibcode=2005DDA....36.0205H}}</ref> This shows that the effects of the galactic tide are quite complex, and depend heavily on the behaviour of individual objects within a planetary system. However, cumulatively, the effect can be quite significant; up to 90% of all comets originating from an Oort cloud may be the result of the galactic tide.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Periodic variation of Oort Cloud flux and cometary impacts on the Earth and Jupiter|author1=Nurmi P. |author2=Valtonen M.J. |author3=Zheng J.Q. |journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|volume=327 | issue=4|pages=1367\u20131376|date=2001|bibcode=2001MNRAS.327.1367N | doi=10.1046/j.1365-8711.2001.04854.x|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Oort cloud]]\n*[[Roche limit]]\n*[[Satellite galaxy]]\n*[[Dwarf galaxy]]\n*[[Interacting galaxy]]\n*[[Tidal force]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Galaxy}}\n\n[[Category:Extragalactic astronomy]]\n[[Category:Interacting galaxies|*]]\n[[Category:Oort cloud]]\n[[Category:Tides]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Tidal force experienced by objects subject to the gravitational field of a galaxy}}\n[[Image:NGC4676.jpg|thumb|300 px|The [[Mice Galaxies]] NGC 4676]]\n\nA '''galactic tide''' is a [[tidal force]] experienced by objects subject to the [[gravitational field]] of a [[galaxy]] such as the [[Milky Way]]. Particular areas of interest concerning galactic tides include [[Interacting galaxy|galactic collisions]], the disruption of [[dwarf galaxy|dwarf]] or [[satellite galaxy|satellite galaxies]], and the Milky Way's tidal effect on the [[Oort cloud]] of the [[Solar System]].\n\n==Effects on external galaxies==\n{{main|Interacting galaxy}}\n\n=== Galaxy collisions ===\n[[File:NGC40384039 large.jpg|thumb|200 px|The lengthy tidal tails of the colliding [[antennae galaxies]]]] \nTidal forces are dependent on the gradient of a gravitational field, rather than its strength, and so tidal effects are usually limited to the immediate surroundings of a galaxy. Two large galaxies undergoing collisions or passing nearby each other will be subjected to very large tidal forces, often producing the most visually striking demonstrations of galactic tides in action.\n\nTwo interacting galaxies will not always collide head-on (if at all), and the tidal forces will distort each galaxy along an axis pointing roughly towards  and away from its perturber. As the two galaxies briefly orbit each other, these distorted regions, which are pulled away from the main body of each galaxy, will be sheared by the galaxy's [[differential rotation]] and flung off into [[intergalactic space]], forming '''tidal tails'''. Such tails are typically strongly curved. If a tail appears to be straight, it is probably being viewed edge-on. The stars and gas that comprise the tails will have been pulled from the easily distorted galactic discs (or other extremities) of one or both bodies, rather than the gravitationally bound galactic centres.<ref name=\"toomre72\">{{cite journal|title=Galactic Bridges and Tails|author1=Toomre A. |author2=Toomre J. |journal=The Astrophysical Journal|volume=178|pages=623\u2013666|date=1972|bibcode=1972ApJ...178..623T|doi=10.1086/151823 }}</ref> Two very prominent examples of collisions producing tidal tails are the [[Mice Galaxies]] and the [[Antennae Galaxies]].\n\nJust as the Moon raises two water tides on opposite sides of the Earth, so a galactic tide produces two arms in its galactic companion. While a large tail is formed if the perturbed galaxy is equal to or less massive than its partner, if it is significantly more massive than the perturbing galaxy, then the trailing arm will be relatively minor, and the leading arm, sometimes called a '''bridge''', will be more prominent.<ref name=\"toomre72\"/> Tidal bridges are typically harder to distinguish than tidal tails: in the first instance, the bridge may be absorbed by the passing galaxy or the resulting merged galaxy, making it visible for a shorter duration than a typical large tail. Secondly, if one of the two galaxies is in the foreground, then the second galaxy \u2014 and the bridge between them \u2014 may be partially obscured. Together, these effects can make it hard to see where one galaxy ends and the next begins. '''Tidal loops''', where a tail joins with its parent galaxy at both ends, are rarer still.<ref>{{cite journal|title=NGC 3310 and its tidal debris: remnants of galaxy evolution|author=Wehner E.H.|display-authors=etal|journal=[[Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society]]|volume=371|issue=3|pages=1047\u20131056|date=2006|bibcode=2006MNRAS.371.1047W|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2966.2006.10757.x |arxiv = astro-ph/0607088 }}</ref>\n\n=== Satellite interactions ===\n[[Image:M31bobo.jpg|thumb|left|300 px|The [[Andromeda Galaxy]]. Note its satellite galaxy [[Messier 32|M32]] at the top left, just above the edge of Andromeda's disk, whose outer arms have been stripped away by Andromeda's tidal forces.]]\nBecause tidal effects are strongest in the immediate vicinity of a galaxy, satellite galaxies are particularly likely to be affected. Such an external force upon a satellite can produce ordered motions within it, leading to large-scale observable effects: the interior structure and motions of a dwarf satellite galaxy may be severely affected by a galactic tide, inducing rotation (as with the tides of the Earth's oceans) or an anomalous mass-to-[[Luminosity#In astronomy|luminosity]] ratio.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Can Galactic Tides Inflate the Apparent M/L's of Dwarf Galaxies?|author1=Piatek S. |author2=Pryor C. |journal=Bulletin of the American Astronomical Society|volume=25|pages=1383|date=1993|bibcode=1993AAS...183.5701P}}</ref> Satellite galaxies can also be subjected to the same tidal stripping that occurs in galactic collisions, where stars and gas are torn from the extremities of a galaxy, possibly to be absorbed by its companion. The dwarf galaxy [[Messier 32|M32]], a satellite galaxy of [[Andromeda Galaxy|Andromeda]], may have lost its [[spiral arm]]s to tidal stripping, while a high star formation rate in the remaining core may be the result of tidally-induced motions of the remaining [[molecular cloud]]s<ref name=\"Bekkietal2001\">{{cite journal\n  | author1=Bekki, Kenji\n  | author2=Couch, Warrick J.\n  | author3=Drinkwater, Michael J.\n  | author4=Gregg, Michael D.\n  | authorlink2=Warrick Couch\n  | title=A New Formation Model for M32: A Threshed Early-Type Spiral Galaxy?\n  | journal=The Astrophysical Journal\n  | date=2001\n  | volume=557\n  | issue=1\n  | pages=Issue 1, pp. L39\u2013L42\n  | bibcode=2001ApJ...557L..39B\n  | doi=10.1086/323075 |arxiv = astro-ph/0107117 | url=http://espace.library.uq.edu.au/view/UQ:37514/UQ37514_OA.pdf\n  }}</ref> (Because tidal forces can knead and compress the interstellar gas clouds inside galaxies, they induce large amounts of [[star formation]] in small satellites.)\n\nThe stripping mechanism is the same as between two comparable galaxies, although its comparatively weak gravitational field ensures that only the satellite, not the host galaxy, is affected. If the satellite is very small compared to the host, the tidal debris tails produced are likely to be symmetric, and follow a very similar orbit, effectively tracing the satellite's path.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Johnston, K.V. |author2=Hernquist, L. |author3=Bolte, M. |title=Fossil Signatures of Ancient Accretion Events in the Halo|journal=The Astrophysical Journal|date=1996|volume=465|pages=278|bibcode=1996ApJ...465..278J|doi=10.1086/177418 |arxiv = astro-ph/9602060 }}</ref> However, if the satellite is reasonably large\u2014typically over one ten thousandth the mass of its host\u2014then the satellite's own gravity may affect the tails, breaking the symmetry and accelerating the tails in different directions. The resulting structure is dependent on both the mass and orbit of the satellite, and the mass and structure of the conjectured [[Dark matter halo|galactic halo]] around the host, and may provide a means of probing the [[dark matter]] [[Potential energy#Gravitational potential|potential]] of a galaxy such as the Milky Way.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Choi, J.-H. |author2=Weinberg, M.D. |author3=Katz, N. |title=The dynamics of tidal tails from massive satellites |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2966.2007.12313.x |date=2007 |journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society |volume=381 |issue=3 |pages=987\u20131000 |arxiv=astro-ph/0702353|bibcode = 2007MNRAS.381..987C }}</ref>\n\nOver many orbits of its parent galaxy, or if the orbit passes too close to it, a dwarf satellite may eventually be completely disrupted, to form a tidal stream of stars and gas wrapping around the larger body. It has been suggested that the extended discs of gas and stars around some galaxies, such as Andromeda, may be the result of the complete tidal disruption (and subsequent merger with the parent galaxy) of a dwarf satellite galaxy.<ref>{{cite journal| title=On the Formation of Extended Galactic Disks by Tidally Disrupted Dwarf Galaxies|author1=Pe\u00f1arrubia J. |author2=McConnachie A. |author3=Babul A. | journal=The Astrophysical Journal| volume=650|issue=1|pages=L33\u2013L36|date=2006|bibcode=2006ApJ...650L..33P| doi=10.1086/508656|arxiv = astro-ph/0606101 }}</ref>\n\n==Effects on bodies within a galaxy==\n{{See also|Oort cloud#Tidal effects}}\n{{refimprove section|date=April 2015}}\nTidal effects are also present within a galaxy, where their gradients are likely to be steepest. This can have consequences for the formation of [[star]]s and [[planetary system]]s. Typically a star's gravity will dominate within its own system, with only the passage of other stars substantially affecting dynamics. However, at the outer reaches of the system, the star's gravity is weak and galactic tides may be significant. In the Solar System, the hypothetical [[Oort cloud]], believed to be the source of long-period [[comet]]s, lies in this transitional region.\n\n[[Image:Kuiper oort-en.svg|thumb|upright=1.3|Diagram of the [[Oort cloud]].]]\n\nThe Oort cloud is believed to be a vast shell surrounding the Solar System, possibly over a [[light-year]] in radius. Across such a vast distance, the gradient of the Milky Way's gravitational field plays a far more noticeable role. Because of this gradient, galactic tides may then deform an otherwise spherical Oort cloud, stretching the cloud in the direction of the galactic centre and compressing it along the other two axes, just as the Earth distends in response to the gravity of the Moon.\n\nThe Sun's gravity is sufficiently weak at such a distance that these small galactic perturbations may be enough to dislodge some [[planetesimals]] from such distant orbits, sending them towards the Sun and planets by significantly reducing their [[perihelia]].<ref>{{cite journal| title=Long-term effects of the Galactic tide on cometary dynamics| author=Fouchard M.| display-authors=etal| journal=Celestial Mechanics and Dynamical Astronomy| volume=95| issue=1\u20134|pages=299\u2013326|date=2006|bibcode=2006CeMDA..95..299F| doi=10.1007/s10569-006-9027-8}}</ref> Such a body, being composed of a rock and ice mixture, would become a comet when subjected to the increased solar radiation present in the inner Solar System.\n\nIt has been suggested that the galactic tide may also contribute to the formation of an Oort cloud, by increasing the perihelia of planetesimals with large [[Apsis|aphelia]].<ref>{{cite journal| title=Orbital Evolution of Planetesimals by the Galactic Tide|author1=Higuchi A., Kokubo E.  |author2=Mukai, T.| journal=Bulletin of the American Astronomical Society| volume=37|pages=521|date=2005|bibcode=2005DDA....36.0205H}}</ref> This shows that the effects of the galactic tide are quite complex, and depend heavily on the behaviour of individual objects within a planetary system. However, cumulatively, the effect can be quite significant; up to 90% of all comets originating from an Oort cloud may be the result of the galactic tide.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Periodic variation of Oort Cloud flux and cometary impacts on the Earth and Jupiter|author1=Nurmi P. |author2=Valtonen M.J. |author3=Zheng J.Q. |journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|volume=327 | issue=4|pages=1367\u20131376|date=2001|bibcode=2001MNRAS.327.1367N | doi=10.1046/j.1365-8711.2001.04854.x|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Oort cloud]]\n*[[Roche limit]]\n*[[Satellite galaxy]]\n*[[Dwarf galaxy]]\n*[[Interacting galaxy]]\n*[[Tidal force]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Galaxy}}\n\n[[Category:Extragalactic astronomy]]\n[[Category:Interacting galaxies|*]]\n[[Category:Oort cloud]]\n[[Category:Tides]]\n", "name_user": "Jim.henderson", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGalaxy collisions:More a matter of how often, than of how much", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galactic_tide"}
{"title_page": "Tronador (rocket)", "text_new": "{{Infobox rocket\n|name = Tronador II\n|image = Cohete Tronador II.JPG\n|imsize = 250\n|caption = ''Tronador II'' rocket [[mockup]] at [[Tecn\u00f3polis]]\n|function = Orbital [[launch vehicle]]\n|manufacturer = [[Comisi\u00f3n Nacional de Actividades Espaciales]]\n|country-origin = [[Argentina]]\n|height = 28 m (~92 ft)\n|alt-height = \n|diameter = 2.5 m\n|alt-diameter = \n|mass = 67000 kg (including propellant)\n|alt-mass = \n|stages = 3\n|LEO-payload = {{convert|250|kg|abbr=on}}\n|alt-LEO = Polar orbit\n|status = Under development\n|sites = [[Puerto Belgrano Naval Base]]\n|launches = \n|fail = \n|first = 2019 (projected)\n|boosters = \n|boostername = \n|boosterengines = \n|boostertime = \n|boosterthrust = \n|alt-boosterthrust = \n|boosterSI = \n|boosterfuel = \n|stage1engines = 3 * T30\n|stage1name = Lower stage\n|stage1time = \n|stage1thrust = 3 \u00d7 30000 kg\n|alt-stage1thrust = \n|stage1SI = \n|stage1fuel = [[LOX]] / [[RP-1]]\n|stage2engines = 1 * other or T4R\n|stage2name = Upper stage\n|stage2time = \n|stage2thrust = 1400 to 4000 kg\n|alt-stage2thrust = \n|stage2SI = \n|stage2fuel = [[Monomethylhydrazine]](MMH) / {{N2O4}}\n}}\n\n'''Tronador''' (Spanish for '''Thunderer''') is a series of Argentine [[rocket]]s, including the Tronador I and [[Tronador II]] vehicles, to develop a [[liquid-propellant rocket]] [[expendable launch system]] called ISCUL<ref>{{cite journal |title=La Facultad de Ingenier\u00eda participar\u00e1 en el desarrollo del |journal=Proyectarse |date=December 2008 |volume=15 |issue=71 |pages=20\u201322 |url=http://www.ing.unlp.edu.ar/institucional/difusion/publicaciones/archivos/proyectarse71.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=2014-08-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821215900/http://www.ing.unlp.edu.ar/institucional/difusion/publicaciones/archivos/proyectarse71.pdf |archivedate=2014-08-21 }}</ref> (''Inyector Satelital de Cargas Utiles Ligeras'', Light Payloads Satellite Launcher).\n\nThe Tronador I is an unguided liquid-fueled rocket<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://www.conae.gov.ar/index.php/espanol/acceso-al-espacio/tronador-ii |title=Comisi\u00f3n Nacional de Actividades Espaciales - Tronador II |website=Conae.gov.ar |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref> used for [[sub-orbital spaceflight]] test flights. Its development led to the larger ''VEx'' test rocket, testing technologies needed for the Tronador II, which has a guidance system and would be capable of reaching [[low Earth orbit]].<ref name=autogenerated2/> Development of the satellite launch vehicle has cost more than 600 million dollars over several years.\n\n==Tronador I==\nThe Tronador I is an unguided liquid-fueled rocket<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/> used for [[sub-orbital spaceflight]] test flights.\n\n===Tronador I (T1)===\nThe Tronador I (T1) vehicle was flown successfully on June 6, 2007<ref name=\"conae.gov.ar\">{{cite web|url=http://www.conae.gov.ar/index.php/espanol/acceso-al-espacio/tronador |title=Comisi\u00f3n Nacional de Actividades Espaciales - Tronador |website=Conae.gov.ar |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref> from [[Puerto Belgrano Naval Base]] near [[Bah\u00eda Blanca]],<ref name=\"conae.gov.ar\"/><ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://grandprix.forochile.org/t80p15-primeras-imagenes-del-lanzador-tronador-ii |title=free forum : grandprix |website=Grandprix.forochile.org |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref> in the south east of the [[Buenos Aires Province]]. This was the first flight of a technology demonstrator vehicle for the program.\n\n====Characteristics====\n* Length: 3,400&nbsp;mm\n* Stages: 1\n* Total takeoff mass: 60&nbsp;kg\n* Payload mass: 4&nbsp;kg\n* Thrust (x 10 s): 500 [[kgf]]\n\n===Tronador Ib (T2)===\nThe Tronador Ib (T2) vehicle was flown successfully on August 5, 2008<ref name=\"conae.gov.ar\"/> from Puerto Belgrano Naval Base.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> This was the second technology demonstrator vehicle flown for the program.\n\n====Characteristics====\n* Length: 3,400&nbsp;mm\n* Stages: 1\n* Total takeoff mass: 60&nbsp;kg\n* Payload mass: 4&nbsp;kg\n* Apogee: 15~20&nbsp;km\n* Thrust (10 s): 1,500 kgf\n\n===VS-30===\nThis was the first cooperative test flight between [[Comisi\u00f3n Nacional de Actividades Espaciales]] and [[Brazilian Space Agency]]; it was successfully flown in December 2007 (Operacion Angicos).<ref>{{Citation needed|date=August 2014}}</ref> The payload built by [[CONAE]], carried several experiments to validate subsystems for the program such as: IMU (Inertial Measurements Unit, that used I[[Fibre optic gyroscope|FOG]]'s), GPS receptor (for navigation), all integrated into the on-board computer, and an attitude control system via cold-gas thrusters. The payload unit completed a suborbital flight carried by an AEB-built VS-30 solid-propellant rocket booster, and was then recovered from the sea after landing with parachutes.\n\n====Characteristics====\n* Length: 3,288&nbsp;mm (Payload module)\n* Stages: 1 (VS-30 booster)\n* Total takeoff mass: 1,500&nbsp;kg\n* Payload mass: 242.1&nbsp;kg\n* Apogee: 120~160&nbsp;km\n* Specific Impulse: 266 s (VS-30 booster)\n\n==Tronador II==\nTronador II's maiden orbital launch is expected to fly in 2019, from Puerto Belgrano Naval Base.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_lau/tronador-2.htm|title=Tronador-2|website=Space.skyrocket.de|access-date=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n\n===Characteristics===\nAs of June 2016, the proposed Tronador II configuration:<ref>http://www.conae.gov.ar/index.php/espanol/acceso-al-espacio/tronador-ii</ref>\n\n* Length: 28 m\n* Stages: 2\n* Diameter: 2.5 m \n* Empty mass: 5,100&nbsp;kg\n* Total weight: 67,000&nbsp;kg\n* Payload mass: 250&nbsp;kg<ref name=Vex1B/>\n* Apogee: 600&nbsp;km\n* Lower Stage: 90t total thrust (3x30t engines) at sea level. Fuel: RP-1/LOX\n* Upper stage: 1.4t to 4t thrust (single pressurized engine) at sea level (2t to 5.5t in vacuum). Fuel:  Monomethylhydrazine(MMH) / {{N2O4}}\n\n===Other proposals===\nThe initial proposal was for a 3-stage rocket. In early 2015, an evolved configuration<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.b14643.de/Spacerockets_1/Rest_World/Tronador-LSA/Description/Frame.htm |title=Tronador LSA |website=B14643.de |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref> was presented at the 52nd Committee on Peaceful Uses of Ultra-Terrestrial Space meeting<ref>{{cite web| url=http://argentinaenelespacio.blogspot.com.ar/2015/02/nuevo-diseno-para-el-tronador-ii.html#more |title=Argentina en el Espacio: \u00bfNuevo dise\u00f1o para el Tronador II? |website=Argentinaenelespacio.blogspot.com.ar |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref> and at the [[Punta Indio]] test launch pad.\n\n* First Stage: 90,000&nbsp;kg (3x30,000&nbsp;kg)\n* Second Stage: 30,000&nbsp;kg\n* Third stage: 4,000&nbsp;kg thrust\n\n<gallery>\nCohete Tronador II.JPG\nMaqueta del Tronador II en el Puerto espacial de Punta Indio.jpg\nTronador II.jpg\nPiramidetronador-tecn\u00f3polis.JPG\nTecn\u00f3polis cohete Tronador II.JPG\nTronadorIMPTecnopolis.JPG\nTronador2B.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n=== Tronador II prototypes ===\n\n====T4000====\nThe T4000 (Tronador T4000 pathfinder rocket) test rocket is related to the project, as it is the basis of the 3rd stage of the Tronador II.<ref name=\"conae.gov.ar\"/> Specifically, it was intended to house the [[attitude control]] system (\u201cThrust Vector Control\u201d - TVS).<ref name=autogenerated3 /> The first launch attempt in 2011 failed.<ref>{{cite web|author=Brazilian Space |url=http://brazilianspace.blogspot.pt/2011/12/informacao-extraoficial-confirma-falha.html |title=BRAZILIAN SPACE: Informa\u00e7\u00e3o Extraoficial Confirma Falha do Foguete T-4000 |website=Brazilianspace.blogspot.pt |date=2013-05-03 |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref>\n\n;Characteristics\n* Diameter: 4.38 m <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b14643.de/Spacerockets_1/Rest_World/Tronador-LSA/Gallery/T-4000.htm |title=T-4000, Gallery |website=B14643.de |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref>\n* Thrust:  4,000&nbsp;kg (~40&nbsp;kN)\n* Impulse time: 10 seconds<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\n====VEx====\n\nThe recent strategy was to fly separately several suborbital experimental subsystems, called \"VEx\", before they are incorporated in the prototype of the Tronador II rocket.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/><ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|url=http://www.portinos.com/14577/escalera-al-cielo-peldano-a-peldano-serie-tronador-ii |title=Escalera al cielo, pelda\u00f1o a pelda\u00f1o (Serie Tronador II) |website=Portinos.com |date=2015-03-18 |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite web|url=http://forum.nasaspaceflight.com/index.php?topic=26645.15 |title=Argentina's SLV development |website=Forum.nasaspaceflight.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.mecon.gov.ar/pnip/basehome/invpub_res.php?pagina=290&jur=35&saf=106&loc=todas&estado=todas&finfun=todas&proc=todas&plan=todas |title=Proyecto de Inversi\u00f3n P\u00fablica. Secretar\u00eda de Pol\u00edtica Econ\u00f3mica |website=Mecon.gov.ar |date=2015-11-30 |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://forum.nasaspaceflight.com/index.php?topic=26645.30 |title=Argentina's SLV development |website=Forum.nasaspaceflight.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite web|last=Rey |first=Patricia |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/argentina-put-first-satellite-space-using-own-launch-technology-2015-1471090 |title=Argentina To Put First Satellite In Space Using Own Launch Technology By 2015 |website=Ibtimes.com |date=2013-10-14 |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref> After a few launches, it was decided in 2017 to stop the experimental Vex series as enough data was obtained to go ahead with a prototype rocket.<ref name=\"varottotss\">{{cite news|author1=Bruno Massare|title=Varotto: \u201cA fines del a\u00f1o que viene deber\u00edamos tener un lanzador satelital\u201d|url=http://www.unsam.edu.ar/tss/varotto-a-fines-del-ano-que-viene-deberiamos-tener-un-lanzador-satelital/|accessdate=31 January 2018|agency=TSS|language=spanish|quote=Decidimos interrumpir el desarrollo de los veh\u00edculos experimentales (la serie VEX) porque consideramos que con lo ya hecho no \u00edbamos a aportar mucho m\u00e1s con otro experimental que lo que aportar\u00eda el modelo tecnol\u00f3gico.}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nVex1APipinas.jpg|VEx-1A\nVex-1b.JPG|VEx-1B\nVEx 5-A at the launch pad.jpg|VEx-5A\n</gallery>\n\n=====VEx-1A=====\nIn March 2014, a suborbital prototype named VEx-1A failed during launch from [[Pipinas]], [[Punta Indio Partido]].<ref name=autogenerated2/><ref name=autogenerated5 /><ref name=autogenerated6>{{cite web|url=http://www.colonbuenosaires.com.ar/semanariocolondoce/cgi-bin/hoy/archivo/2012a/00000663.html |title=Cohete Tronador II: m\u00e1s que un monumento de Tecn\u00f3polis |website=Colonbuenosaires.com.ar |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infobae.com/2013/11/09/1522422-argentina-lanzara-un-cohete-diseno-nacional-que-pondra-orbita-satelites-observacion |title=Argentina lanzar\u00e1 un cohete de dise\u00f1o nacional que pondr\u00e1 en \u00f3rbita sat\u00e9lites de observaci\u00f3n |website=Infobae.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref> It had only one stage, weigh 2.8 tonnes, thrust of 4 ton, 60 seconds mission duration, expected apogee of 2&nbsp;km. VEx-1A first launch attempt was postponed in December 2013 due to ground support equipment fail. The second attempt failed on February 26, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://puntaindioweb.com/el-cohete-despego-y-exploto.htm |title=El cohete despeg\u00f3 y explot\u00f3 |publisher=Punta Indio Web |date=2014-02-26 |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1669921-un-despegue-fallido |title=Un despegue fallido - 07.03.2014 - LA NACION |website=Lanacion.com.ar |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref> It was discovered that the failure was caused by interferences between the launch pad and the rocket, which prevented the vehicle from elevating more than 2m off the ground. The engine control mechanism shut off the fuel valve, preventing an explosion, and the rocket fell down next to the pad.\n\n=====VEx-1B=====\nThe first flight of this suborbital vehicle was on 15 August 2014 from [[Pipinas]], [[Punta Indio Partido]].<ref name=Vex1B>{{cite web|url=http://www.conae.gov.ar/index.php/espanol/2014 |title=Comisi\u00f3n Nacional de Actividades Espaciales - 2014 |website=Conae.gov.ar |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref> It successfully tested propulsion, control, and navigation subsystems. 2,200 m apogee, 27 seconds flight time. It landed in the sea assisted by the recovery parachutes. The vehicle was recovered and examined to determine whether further VEx-1 test rockets are required or if a VEx-2 flight should be implemented.\n\n=====VEx-5A=====\nVEx-5A was a two stage suborbital rocket that was destroyed upon launch. The T-10 first stage is capable of producing 11t of thrust, while the T-4 second stage is capable of 4t of thrust. The rocket was 18 meters long and 1.5 meters diameter, with a total launch weight (including fuel) of 8500&nbsp;kg.<ref>http://www.perfil.com/ciencia/Planean-mas-pruebas-para-el-lanzador-de-satelites-argentino--20160312-0062.html</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.b14643.de/Spacerockets_1/Rest_World/Tronador-LSA/Description/Frame.htm|title=Tronador LSA|website=www.b14643.de|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref> The rocket would have separated from the first stage (the propellants are [[liquid oxygen]]/[[RP-1]]) at 15 km altitude and the second stage would have continued, reaching up to 30 km altitude using [[hydrazine]]/[[nitric acid]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?sl=auto&tl=en&js=y&prev=_t&hl=en&ie=UTF-8&u=https://www.clarin.com/politica/vex-lanzan-tercer-experimental-argentino_0_rJ76_s-zl.html&edit-text=|title=Google Translate|website=translate.google.com|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref> The vehicle would have tested several technologies, new fuels, and for the first time, the separation of two stages rocket (mechanical and automatic aspects), and the ignition of the second stage in flight. The rocket was completed in mid 2015 and scheduled to launch in October 2015, and then November 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pagina12.com.ar/diario/economia/2-309070-2016-09-10.html|title=P\u00e1gina/12 :: Econom\u00eda :: Una foto junto al cohete heredado|website=www.pagina12.com.ar|access-date=2016-09-30}}</ref> The test flight finally occurred on 21 April 2017, 18:00 local time from [[Pipinas]], [[Punta Indio Partido]]. The rocket climbed up from its pad, but eight seconds later the first stage rocket engine shut down due to abrupt flow in its fuel lines. Several seconds later, the rocket fell and impacted the launch pad, causing a fiery explosion. The ill-fated launch was announced officially by CONAE several hours after the launch and footage from several angles were made available.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=es&tl=en&u=https://www.clarin.com/sociedad/video-cohete-lanzado-punta-indio-problemas-estrello_0_BkO1ZgYRl.html|title=Google Translate|website=translate.google.com|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=es&tl=en&u=https://ultimahora.es/noticias/internacional/2017/04/29/264322/vehiculo-experimental-argentino-estrella-nada-mas-despegar.html|title=Google Translate|website=translate.google.com|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=es&tl=en&u=http://www.politicargentina.com/notas/201704/20575-exclusivo-el-gobierno-oculto-la-explosion-de-un-cohete-lanzado-por-conae.html|title=Google Translate|website=translate.google.com|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=auto&tl=en&u=http://ren.tv/novosti/2017-04-29/video-vzryva-rakety-vex-5-pri-zapuske-v-argentine-poyavilos-v-seti|title=Google Translate|website=translate.google.com|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref>\n\n=====VEx-5B=====\nTest flight - single stage 30t thrust engine rocket - it was projected for a 2018 launch from [[Pipinas]], [[Punta Indio Partido]]. The mission was cancelled in 2017. <ref name=\"varottotss\"/>\n\n=====VEx-5C=====\nTest flight - two stage test rocket. First stage 30t thrust engine, second stage VEx-1 engine - it was projected for a 2019 launch from [[Puerto Belgrano Naval Base]].<ref name=\"energypress.com.ar\">{{cite web|url=http://www.energypress.com.ar/index.php?r=noticias/verNoticia&q=76271|title=El INVAP de Bariloche ya prepara el Arsat 2 y 3 para 2015 y 2017|author=|date=|website=Energypress.com.ar|accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref><ref name=\"machtres.com\">{{cite web|url=http://machtres.com/vex1.html|title=VEX1 - Machtres Aeronautica y Espacio|date=2014-09-25|website=Machtres.com|accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref><ref name=\"space.skyrocket.de\">http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_lau/vex-5.htm</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://forum.nasaspaceflight.com/index.php?topic=26645.60 |title=Argentina's SLV development |website=Forum.nasaspaceflight.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref> The mission was cancelled in 2017.<ref name=\"varottotss\"/>\n\n==Tronador III==\n\nThe proposed Tronador III would have the same diameter as Tronador II, but would have a length of {{convert|34|m}}. The fueled rocket would weight 89 metric tons, and capable of delivering a ton of payload into polar orbit.<ref name=\"exposicionvarottohotelt3\">{{cite web|author1=Conrado Varotto|title=Plan Espacial Nacional - 27 de Agosto de 2015 - Seminario DAR|url=http://www.desarrolloargentino.org/sites/default/files/download/dr._conrado_varotto.pdf|accessdate=1 February 2018|date=27 August 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304102510/http://www.desarrolloargentino.org/sites/default/files/download/dr._conrado_varotto.pdf|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of rockets]]\n* [[Comparison of orbital launch systems]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.rocket.com.ar/biblioteca/databases/download/Proyecto_Rocket Rocket.com.br]\n* {{cite web|url=http://grandprix.forochile.org/t80p15-primeras-imagenes-del-lanzador-tronador-ii |title=Free forum : grandprix |website=Grandprix.forochile.org |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_lau/tronador-2.htm |title=Tronador-2 |website=Space.skyrocket.de |date=2015-11-14 |accessdate=2015-12-20}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.ctys.com.ar/index.php?idPage=20&idArticulo=1934 |title=Agencia CTyS |website=Ctys.com.ar |date=2012-07-17 |accessdate=2015-12-20}}\n\n{{Argentina space program}}\n{{Orbital launch systems}}\n\n[[Category:Sounding rockets of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Space programme of Argentina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rocket\n|name = Tronador II\n|image = Cohete Tronador II.JPG\n|imsize = 250\n|caption = ''Tronador II'' rocket [[mockup]] at [[Tecn\u00f3polis]]\n|function = Orbital [[launch vehicle]]\n|manufacturer = [[Comisi\u00f3n Nacional de Actividades Espaciales]]\n|country-origin = [[Argentina]]\n|height = 28 m (~92 ft)\n|alt-height = \n|diameter = 2.5 m\n|alt-diameter = \n|mass = 67000 kg (including propellant)\n|alt-mass = \n|stages = 3\n|LEO-payload = {{convert|250|kg|abbr=on}}\n|alt-LEO = Polar orbit\n|status = Under development\n|sites = [[Puerto Belgrano Naval Base]]\n|launches = \n|fail = \n|first = 2019 (projected)\n|boosters = \n|boostername = \n|boosterengines = \n|boostertime = \n|boosterthrust = \n|alt-boosterthrust = \n|boosterSI = \n|boosterfuel = \n|stage1engines = 3 * T30\n|stage1name = Lower stage\n|stage1time = \n|stage1thrust = 3 \u00d7 30000 kg\n|alt-stage1thrust = \n|stage1SI = \n|stage1fuel = [[LOX]] / [[RP-1]]\n|stage2engines = 1 * other or T4R\n|stage2name = Upper stage\n|stage2time = \n|stage2thrust = 1400 to 4000 kg\n|alt-stage2thrust = \n|stage2SI = \n|stage2fuel = [[Monomethylhydrazine]](MMH) / {{N2O4}}\n}}\n\n'''Tronador''' (Spanish for '''Thunderer''') is a series of Argentine [[rocket]]s, including the Tronador I and [[Tronador II]] vehicles, to develop a [[liquid-propellant rocket]] [[expendable launch system]] called ISCUL<ref>{{cite journal |title=La Facultad de Ingenier\u00eda participar\u00e1 en el desarrollo del |journal=Proyectarse |date=December 2008 |volume=15 |issue=71 |pages=20\u201322 |url=http://www.ing.unlp.edu.ar/institucional/difusion/publicaciones/archivos/proyectarse71.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=2014-08-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821215900/http://www.ing.unlp.edu.ar/institucional/difusion/publicaciones/archivos/proyectarse71.pdf |archivedate=2014-08-21 }}</ref> (''Inyector Satelital de Cargas Utiles Ligeras'', Light Payloads Satellite Launcher).\n\nThe Tronador I is an unguided liquid-fueled rocket<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://www.conae.gov.ar/index.php/espanol/acceso-al-espacio/tronador-ii |title=Comisi\u00f3n Nacional de Actividades Espaciales - Tronador II |website=Conae.gov.ar |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref> used for [[sub-orbital spaceflight]] test flights. Its development led to the larger ''VEx'' test rocket, testing technologies needed for the Tronador II, which has a guidance system and would be capable of reaching [[low Earth orbit]].<ref name=autogenerated2/> Development of the satellite launch vehicle has cost more than 600 million dollars over several years.\n\n==Tronador I==\nThe Tronador I is an unguided liquid-fueled rocket<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/> used for [[sub-orbital spaceflight]] test flights.\n\n===Tronador I (T1)===\nThe Tronador I (T1) vehicle was flown successfully on June 6, 2007<ref name=\"conae.gov.ar\">{{cite web|url=http://www.conae.gov.ar/index.php/espanol/acceso-al-espacio/tronador |title=Comisi\u00f3n Nacional de Actividades Espaciales - Tronador |website=Conae.gov.ar |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref> from [[Puerto Belgrano Naval Base]] near [[Bah\u00eda Blanca]],<ref name=\"conae.gov.ar\"/><ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://grandprix.forochile.org/t80p15-primeras-imagenes-del-lanzador-tronador-ii |title=free forum : grandprix |website=Grandprix.forochile.org |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref> in the south east of the [[Buenos Aires Province]]. This was the first flight of a technology demonstrator vehicle for the program.\n\n====Characteristics====\n* Length: 3,400&nbsp;mm\n* Stages: 1\n* Total takeoff mass: 60&nbsp;kg\n* Payload mass: 4&nbsp;kg\n* Thrust (x 10 s): 500 [[kgf]]\n\n===Tronador Ib (T2)===\nThe Tronador Ib (T2) vehicle was flown successfully on August 5, 2008<ref name=\"conae.gov.ar\"/> from Puerto Belgrano Naval Base.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> This was the second technology demonstrator vehicle flown for the program.\n\n====Characteristics====\n* Length: 3,400&nbsp;mm\n* Stages: 1\n* Total takeoff mass: 60&nbsp;kg\n* Payload mass: 4&nbsp;kg\n* Apogee: 15~20&nbsp;km\n* Thrust (10 s): 1,500 kgf\n\n===VS-30===\nThis was the first cooperative test flight between [[Comisi\u00f3n Nacional de Actividades Espaciales]] and [[Brazilian Space Agency]]; it was successfully flown in December 2007 (Operacion Angicos).<ref>{{Citation needed|date=August 2014}}</ref> The payload built by [[CONAE]], carried several experiments to validate subsystems for the program such as: IMU (Inertial Measurements Unit, that used I[[Fibre optic gyroscope|FOG]]'s), GPS receptor (for navigation), all integrated into the on-board computer, and an attitude control system via cold-gas thrusters. The payload unit completed a suborbital flight carried by an AEB-built VS-30 solid-propellant rocket booster, and was then recovered from the sea after landing with parachutes.\n\n====Characteristics====\n* Length: 3,288&nbsp;mm (Payload module)\n* Stages: 1 (VS-30 booster)\n* Total takeoff mass: 1,500&nbsp;kg\n* Payload mass: 242.1&nbsp;kg\n* Apogee: 120~160&nbsp;km\n* Specific Impulse: 266 s (VS-30 booster)\n\n==Tronador II==\nTronador II's maiden orbital launch is expected to fly in 2019, from Puerto Belgrano Naval Base.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_lau/tronador-2.htm|title=Tronador-2|website=Space.skyrocket.de|access-date=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n\n===Characteristics===\nAs of June 2016, the proposed Tronador II configuration:<ref>http://www.conae.gov.ar/index.php/espanol/acceso-al-espacio/tronador-ii</ref>\n\n* Length: 28 m\n* Stages: 2\n* Diameter: 2.5 m \n* Empty mass: 5,100&nbsp;kg\n* Total weight: 67,000&nbsp;kg\n* Payload mass: 250&nbsp;kg<ref name=Vex1B/>\n* Apogee: 600&nbsp;km\n* Lower Stage: 90t total thrust (3x30t engines) at sea level. Fuel: RP-1/LOX\n* Upper stage: 1.4t to 4t thrust (single pressurized engine) at sea level (2t to 5.5t in vacuum). Fuel:  Monomethylhydrazine(MMH) / {{N2O4}}\n\n===Other proposals===\nThe initial proposal was for a 3-stage rocket. In early 2015, an evolved configuration<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.b14643.de/Spacerockets_1/Rest_World/Tronador-LSA/Description/Frame.htm |title=Tronador LSA |website=B14643.de |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref> was presented at the 52nd Committee on Peaceful Uses of Ultra-Terrestrial Space meeting<ref>{{cite web| url=http://argentinaenelespacio.blogspot.com.ar/2015/02/nuevo-diseno-para-el-tronador-ii.html#more |title=Argentina en el Espacio: \u00bfNuevo dise\u00f1o para el Tronador II? |website=Argentinaenelespacio.blogspot.com.ar |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref> and at the [[Punta Indio]] test launch pad.\n\n* First Stage: 90,000&nbsp;kg (3x30,000&nbsp;kg)\n* Second Stage: 30,000&nbsp;kg\n* Third stage: 4,000&nbsp;kg thrust\n\n<gallery>\nCohete Tronador II.JPG\nMaqueta del Tronador II en el Puerto espacial de Punta Indio.jpg\nTronador II.jpg\nPiramidetronador-tecn\u00f3polis.JPG\nTecn\u00f3polis cohete Tronador II.JPG\nTronadorIMPTecnopolis.JPG\nTronador2B.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n=== Tronador II prototypes ===\n\n====T4000====\nThe T4000 (Tronador T4000 pathfinder rocket) test rocket is related to the project, as it is the basis of the 3rd stage of the Tronador II.<ref name=\"conae.gov.ar\"/> Specifically, it was intended to house the [[attitude control]] system (\u201cThrust Vector Control\u201d - TVS).<ref name=autogenerated3 /> The first launch attempt in 2011 failed.<ref>{{cite web|author=Brazilian Space |url=http://brazilianspace.blogspot.pt/2011/12/informacao-extraoficial-confirma-falha.html |title=BRAZILIAN SPACE: Informa\u00e7\u00e3o Extraoficial Confirma Falha do Foguete T-4000 |website=Brazilianspace.blogspot.pt |date=2013-05-03 |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref>\n\n;Characteristics\n* Diameter: 4.38 m <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b14643.de/Spacerockets_1/Rest_World/Tronador-LSA/Gallery/T-4000.htm |title=T-4000, Gallery |website=B14643.de |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref>\n* Thrust:  4,000&nbsp;kg (~40&nbsp;kN)\n* Impulse time: 10 seconds<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\n====VEx====\n\nThe recent strategy was to fly separately several suborbital experimental subsystems, called \"VEx\", before they are incorporated in the prototype of the Tronador II rocket.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/><ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|url=http://www.portinos.com/14577/escalera-al-cielo-peldano-a-peldano-serie-tronador-ii |title=Escalera al cielo, pelda\u00f1o a pelda\u00f1o (Serie Tronador II) |website=Portinos.com |date=2015-03-18 |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite web|url=http://forum.nasaspaceflight.com/index.php?topic=26645.15 |title=Argentina's SLV development |website=Forum.nasaspaceflight.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.mecon.gov.ar/pnip/basehome/invpub_res.php?pagina=290&jur=35&saf=106&loc=todas&estado=todas&finfun=todas&proc=todas&plan=todas |title=Proyecto de Inversi\u00f3n P\u00fablica. Secretar\u00eda de Pol\u00edtica Econ\u00f3mica |website=Mecon.gov.ar |date=2015-11-30 |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://forum.nasaspaceflight.com/index.php?topic=26645.30 |title=Argentina's SLV development |website=Forum.nasaspaceflight.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite web|last=Rey |first=Patricia |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/argentina-put-first-satellite-space-using-own-launch-technology-2015-1471090 |title=Argentina To Put First Satellite In Space Using Own Launch Technology By 2015 |website=Ibtimes.com |date=2013-10-14 |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref> After a few launches, it was decided in 2017 to stop the experimental Vex series as enough data was obtained to go ahead with a prototype rocket.<ref name=\"varottotss\">{{cite news|author1=Bruno Massare|title=Varotto: \u201cA fines del a\u00f1o que viene deber\u00edamos tener un lanzador satelital\u201d|url=http://www.unsam.edu.ar/tss/varotto-a-fines-del-ano-que-viene-deberiamos-tener-un-lanzador-satelital/|accessdate=31 January 2018|agency=TSS|language=spanish|quote=Decidimos interrumpir el desarrollo de los veh\u00edculos experimentales (la serie VEX) porque consideramos que con lo ya hecho no \u00edbamos a aportar mucho m\u00e1s con otro experimental que lo que aportar\u00eda el modelo tecnol\u00f3gico.}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nVex1APipinas.jpg|VEx-1A\nVex-1b.JPG|VEx-1B\n2213265w620.jpg|VEx-5A\n</gallery>\n\n=====VEx-1A=====\nIn March 2014, a suborbital prototype named VEx-1A failed during launch from [[Pipinas]], [[Punta Indio Partido]].<ref name=autogenerated2/><ref name=autogenerated5 /><ref name=autogenerated6>{{cite web|url=http://www.colonbuenosaires.com.ar/semanariocolondoce/cgi-bin/hoy/archivo/2012a/00000663.html |title=Cohete Tronador II: m\u00e1s que un monumento de Tecn\u00f3polis |website=Colonbuenosaires.com.ar |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infobae.com/2013/11/09/1522422-argentina-lanzara-un-cohete-diseno-nacional-que-pondra-orbita-satelites-observacion |title=Argentina lanzar\u00e1 un cohete de dise\u00f1o nacional que pondr\u00e1 en \u00f3rbita sat\u00e9lites de observaci\u00f3n |website=Infobae.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref> It had only one stage, weigh 2.8 tonnes, thrust of 4 ton, 60 seconds mission duration, expected apogee of 2&nbsp;km. VEx-1A first launch attempt was postponed in December 2013 due to ground support equipment fail. The second attempt failed on February 26, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://puntaindioweb.com/el-cohete-despego-y-exploto.htm |title=El cohete despeg\u00f3 y explot\u00f3 |publisher=Punta Indio Web |date=2014-02-26 |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1669921-un-despegue-fallido |title=Un despegue fallido - 07.03.2014 - LA NACION |website=Lanacion.com.ar |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref> It was discovered that the failure was caused by interferences between the launch pad and the rocket, which prevented the vehicle from elevating more than 2m off the ground. The engine control mechanism shut off the fuel valve, preventing an explosion, and the rocket fell down next to the pad.\n\n=====VEx-1B=====\nThe first flight of this suborbital vehicle was on 15 August 2014 from [[Pipinas]], [[Punta Indio Partido]].<ref name=Vex1B>{{cite web|url=http://www.conae.gov.ar/index.php/espanol/2014 |title=Comisi\u00f3n Nacional de Actividades Espaciales - 2014 |website=Conae.gov.ar |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref> It successfully tested propulsion, control, and navigation subsystems. 2,200 m apogee, 27 seconds flight time. It landed in the sea assisted by the recovery parachutes. The vehicle was recovered and examined to determine whether further VEx-1 test rockets are required or if a VEx-2 flight should be implemented.\n\n=====VEx-5A=====\nVEx-5A was a two stage suborbital rocket that was destroyed upon launch. The T-10 first stage is capable of producing 11t of thrust, while the T-4 second stage is capable of 4t of thrust. The rocket was 18 meters long and 1.5 meters diameter, with a total launch weight (including fuel) of 8500&nbsp;kg.<ref>http://www.perfil.com/ciencia/Planean-mas-pruebas-para-el-lanzador-de-satelites-argentino--20160312-0062.html</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.b14643.de/Spacerockets_1/Rest_World/Tronador-LSA/Description/Frame.htm|title=Tronador LSA|website=www.b14643.de|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref> The rocket would have separated from the first stage (the propellants are [[liquid oxygen]]/[[RP-1]]) at 15 km altitude and the second stage would have continued, reaching up to 30 km altitude using [[hydrazine]]/[[nitric acid]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?sl=auto&tl=en&js=y&prev=_t&hl=en&ie=UTF-8&u=https://www.clarin.com/politica/vex-lanzan-tercer-experimental-argentino_0_rJ76_s-zl.html&edit-text=|title=Google Translate|website=translate.google.com|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref> The vehicle would have tested several technologies, new fuels, and for the first time, the separation of two stages rocket (mechanical and automatic aspects), and the ignition of the second stage in flight. The rocket was completed in mid 2015 and scheduled to launch in October 2015, and then November 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pagina12.com.ar/diario/economia/2-309070-2016-09-10.html|title=P\u00e1gina/12 :: Econom\u00eda :: Una foto junto al cohete heredado|website=www.pagina12.com.ar|access-date=2016-09-30}}</ref> The test flight finally occurred on 21 April 2017, 18:00 local time from [[Pipinas]], [[Punta Indio Partido]]. The rocket climbed up from its pad, but eight seconds later the first stage rocket engine shut down due to abrupt flow in its fuel lines. Several seconds later, the rocket fell and impacted the launch pad, causing a fiery explosion. The ill-fated launch was announced officially by CONAE several hours after the launch and footage from several angles were made available.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=es&tl=en&u=https://www.clarin.com/sociedad/video-cohete-lanzado-punta-indio-problemas-estrello_0_BkO1ZgYRl.html|title=Google Translate|website=translate.google.com|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=es&tl=en&u=https://ultimahora.es/noticias/internacional/2017/04/29/264322/vehiculo-experimental-argentino-estrella-nada-mas-despegar.html|title=Google Translate|website=translate.google.com|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=es&tl=en&u=http://www.politicargentina.com/notas/201704/20575-exclusivo-el-gobierno-oculto-la-explosion-de-un-cohete-lanzado-por-conae.html|title=Google Translate|website=translate.google.com|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=auto&tl=en&u=http://ren.tv/novosti/2017-04-29/video-vzryva-rakety-vex-5-pri-zapuske-v-argentine-poyavilos-v-seti|title=Google Translate|website=translate.google.com|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref>\n\n=====VEx-5B=====\nTest flight - single stage 30t thrust engine rocket - it was projected for a 2018 launch from [[Pipinas]], [[Punta Indio Partido]]. The mission was cancelled in 2017. <ref name=\"varottotss\"/>\n\n=====VEx-5C=====\nTest flight - two stage test rocket. First stage 30t thrust engine, second stage VEx-1 engine - it was projected for a 2019 launch from [[Puerto Belgrano Naval Base]].<ref name=\"energypress.com.ar\">{{cite web|url=http://www.energypress.com.ar/index.php?r=noticias/verNoticia&q=76271|title=El INVAP de Bariloche ya prepara el Arsat 2 y 3 para 2015 y 2017|author=|date=|website=Energypress.com.ar|accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref><ref name=\"machtres.com\">{{cite web|url=http://machtres.com/vex1.html|title=VEX1 - Machtres Aeronautica y Espacio|date=2014-09-25|website=Machtres.com|accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref><ref name=\"space.skyrocket.de\">http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_lau/vex-5.htm</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://forum.nasaspaceflight.com/index.php?topic=26645.60 |title=Argentina's SLV development |website=Forum.nasaspaceflight.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref> The mission was cancelled in 2017.<ref name=\"varottotss\"/>\n\n==Tronador III==\n\nThe proposed Tronador III would have the same diameter as Tronador II, but would have a length of {{convert|34|m}}. The fueled rocket would weight 89 metric tons, and capable of delivering a ton of payload into polar orbit.<ref name=\"exposicionvarottohotelt3\">{{cite web|author1=Conrado Varotto|title=Plan Espacial Nacional - 27 de Agosto de 2015 - Seminario DAR|url=http://www.desarrolloargentino.org/sites/default/files/download/dr._conrado_varotto.pdf|accessdate=1 February 2018|date=27 August 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304102510/http://www.desarrolloargentino.org/sites/default/files/download/dr._conrado_varotto.pdf|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of rockets]]\n* [[Comparison of orbital launch systems]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.rocket.com.ar/biblioteca/databases/download/Proyecto_Rocket Rocket.com.br]\n* {{cite web|url=http://grandprix.forochile.org/t80p15-primeras-imagenes-del-lanzador-tronador-ii |title=Free forum : grandprix |website=Grandprix.forochile.org |date= |accessdate=2015-12-20}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_lau/tronador-2.htm |title=Tronador-2 |website=Space.skyrocket.de |date=2015-11-14 |accessdate=2015-12-20}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.ctys.com.ar/index.php?idPage=20&idArticulo=1934 |title=Agencia CTyS |website=Ctys.com.ar |date=2012-07-17 |accessdate=2015-12-20}}\n\n{{Argentina space program}}\n{{Orbital launch systems}}\n\n[[Category:Sounding rockets of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Space programme of Argentina]]\n", "name_user": "BugWarp", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File renamed:File:2213265w620.jpg\u2192File:VEx 5-A at the launch pad.jpgMore precise name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tronador_(rocket)"}
{"title_page": "Sir Edmund Bacon, 6th Baronet, of Redgrave", "text_new": "[[File:BaconArms.svg|thumb|150px|Arms of Bacon: ''Gules, on a chief argent two mullets pierced sable''<ref>Montague-Smith, P.W. (ed.), Debrett's Peerage, Baronetage, Knightage and Companionage, Kelly's Directories Ltd, Kingston-upon-Thames, 1968, p.34</ref>]]\n'''Sir Edmund Bacon, 6th Baronet''' (c. 1680 or 1686 \u2013 30 April 1755), of Garboldisham, Norfolk, was a [[Great Britain|British]] politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] between 1710 and 1741.\n\n==Life==\nBacon was the eldest son of Sir Robert Bacon, 5th Baronet and his wife Elizabeth Chandler, daughter of Daniel Chandler.<ref name=Cokayne1>{{Citation |editor-last=Cokayne |editor-first=George Edward |year=1900 |title= Complete Baronetage volume 1 (1611\u20131625) |url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924092524374/page/n23 | volume=1|  location=Exeter |publisher=William Pollard and Co| pages= 1| accessdate = 13 April 2019 }}</ref> He was admitted at [[Pembroke College, Cambridge]] on 5 May 1697.<ref>{{acad|id=BCN697E|name=Bacon, Edmund}}</ref> Bacon succeeded his father as [[baronet]] in 1704.<ref name = Cokayne1/>\n\nIn 1710, Bacon stood as [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Thetford (UK Parliament constituency)|Thetford]], a seat he held until 1713.  He then represented [[Norfolk (UK Parliament constituency)|Norfolk]] from 1713 until 1715, and again from 1728 until 1741.<ref name=HOP2>Sedgwick, R editor. [https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/bacon-sir-edmund-1680-1755 BACON, Sir Edmund, 6th Bt. (c.1680-1755), of Garboldisham, Norfolk].\nPublished in The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1715-1754.1970.</ref>\n\nOn 27 November 1712, Bacon married Mary Kemp, daughter of [[Sir Robert Kemp, 3rd Baronet]] at [[Ubbeston]] in [[Suffolk]].<ref name = Cokayne1/> They had four daughters, but no sons and so with his death the [[baronetcy]] devolved to a descendant of Sir Butts Bacon, 1st Baronet, of Mildenhall, third son of [[Sir Nicholas Bacon, 1st Baronet, of Redgrave]], thus uniting both creations.<ref name = Cokayne1/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Sir Thomas Hanmer, 4th Baronet|Sir Thomas Hanmer]] <br/> [[Dudley North (politician)|Dudley North]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Thetford (UK Parliament constituency)|Thetford]]\n       | with   = [[Dudley North (politician)|Dudley North]]\n       | years  = [[1710 British general election|1710]]\u2013[[1713 British general election|1713]] }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[Sir William Barker, 5th Baronet|Sir William Barker]] <br/> [[Dudley North (politician)|Dudley North]] }}\n\n{{s-bef| before = [[Sir John Wodehouse, 4th Baronet|Sir John Wodehouse]] <br/> [[Sir Jacob Astley, 1st Baronet|Sir Jacob Astley]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Norfolk (UK Parliament constituency)|Norfolk]]\n       | with   = [[Sir Jacob Astley, 1st Baronet|Sir Jacob Astley]]\n       | years  = [[1713 British general election|1713]]\u2013[[1715 British general election|1715]] }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[Thomas de Grey (1680-1765)|Thomas de Grey]] <br/> [[Sir Jacob Astley, 1st Baronet|Sir Jacob Astley]] }}\n\n{{s-bef| before = [[John Hobart, 1st Earl of Buckinghamshire|Sir John Hobart]] <br/> [[Thomas Coke, 1st Earl of Leicester (fifth creation)|Sir Thomas Coke]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Norfolk (UK Parliament constituency)|Norfolk]]\n       | with   = [[Harbord Harbord]] 1728\u20131734\n       | with2  = [[William Wodehouse]] 1734\u20131737\n       | with3  = [[Sir Armine Wodehouse, 5th Baronet|Armine Wodehouse]] 1737\u20131741\n       | years  = 1728\u2013[[1741 British general election|1741]] }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[Sir Armine Wodehouse, 5th Baronet|Armine Wodehouse]] <br/> [[Edward Coke, Viscount Coke|Viscount Coke]] }}\n\n{{s-reg|en-bt}}\n{{s-bef| before = Edmund Bacon }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Bacon baronets|Baronet]] <br/>'''(of Redgrave)'''\n       | years  = 1704\u20131755 }}\n{{s-aft| after  = Richard Bacon }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bacon, Edmund, 06th Baronet}}\n[[Category:1680s births]]\n[[Category:1755 deaths]]\n[[Category:Bacon family|Edmund]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of England]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Pembroke College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for Norfolk]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for Thetford]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1710\u20131713]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1713\u20131715]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1727\u20131734]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1734\u20131741]]\n\n\n{{Baronet-stub}}\n{{England-GreatBritain-MP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:BaconArms.svg|thumb|150px|Arms of Bacon: ''Gules, on a chief argent two mullets pierced sable''<ref>Montague-Smith, P.W. (ed.), Debrett's Peerage, Baronetage, Knightage and Companionage, Kelly's Directories Ltd, Kingston-upon-Thames, 1968, p.34</ref>]]\n'''Sir Edmund Bacon, 6th Baronet''' (c. 1680 or 1686 \u2013 30 April 1755), of Garboldisham, Norfolk, was a [[Great Britain|British]] politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] between 1710 and 1741.\n\n==Life==\nBacon was the eldest son of Sir Robert Bacon, 5th Baronet and his wife Elizabeth Chandler, daughter of Daniel Chandler.<ref name=Cokayne1>{{Citation |editor-last=Cokayne |editor-first=George Edward |year=1900 |title= Complete Baronetage volume 1 (1611\u20131625) |url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924092524374/page/n23 | volume=1|  location=Exeter |publisher=William Pollard and Co| pages= 1| accessdate = 13 April 2019 }}</ref> He was admitted at [[Pembroke College, Cambridge]] on 5 May 1697.<ref>{{acad|id=BCN697E|name=Bacon, Edmund}}</ref> Bacon succeeded his father as [[baronet]] in 1704.<ref name = Cokayne1/>\n\nIn 1710, Bacon stood as [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Thetford (UK Parliament constituency)|Thetford]], a seat he held until 1713.  He then represented [[Norfolk (UK Parliament constituency)|Norfolk]] from 1713 until 1715, and again from 1728 until 1741.<ref name=HOP2>Sedgwick, R editor. [https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/bacon-sir-edmund-1680-1755 BACON, Sir Edmund, 6th Bt. (c.1680-1755), of Garboldisham, Norfolk].\nPublished in The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1715-1754.1970.</ref>\n\nOn 27 November 1712, Bacon married Mary Kemp, daughter of [[Sir Robert Kemp, 3rd Baronet]] at [[Ubbeston]] in [[Suffolk]].<ref name = Cokayne1/> They had four daughters, but no sons and so with his death the [[baronetcy]] devolved to a descendant of Sir Butts Bacon, 1st Baronet, of Mildenhall, third son of [[Sir Nicholas Bacon, 1st Baronet, of Redgrave]], thus uniting both creations.<ref name = Cokayne1/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Sir Thomas Hanmer, 4th Baronet|Sir Thomas Hanmer]] <br/> [[Dudley North (politician)|Dudley North]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Thetford (UK Parliament constituency)|Thetford]]\n       | with   = [[Dudley North (politician)|Dudley North]]\n       | years  = [[1710 British general election|1710]]\u2013[[1713 British general election|1713]] }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[Sir William Barker, 5th Baronet|Sir William Barker]] <br/> [[Dudley North (politician)|Dudley North]] }}\n\n{{s-bef| before = [[Sir John Wodehouse, 4th Baronet|Sir John Wodehouse]] <br/> [[Sir Jacob Astley, 1st Baronet|Sir Jacob Astley]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Norfolk (UK Parliament constituency)|Norfolk]]\n       | with   = [[Sir Jacob Astley, 1st Baronet|Sir Jacob Astley]]\n       | years  = [[1713 British general election|1713]]\u2013[[1715 British general election|1715]] }}\n{{s-aft| after  = [[Thomas de Grey (1680-1765)|Thomas de Grey]] <br/> [[Sir Jacob Astley, 1st Baronet|Sir Jacob Astley]] }}\n\n{{s-bef| before = [[J