{"title_page": "Lower Bavaria", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Lower Bavaria\n| native_name             = Niederbayern\n| native_name_lang        = de\n| settlement_type         = [[Regierungsbezirk]]\n| image_map               = Locator map RB Niederbayern in Bavaria.svg\n| map_caption             = Map of [[Bavaria]] highlighting Lower Bavaria\n| coordinates             = \n| coor_pinpoint           = \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[Germany]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States of Germany|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Bavaria]]\n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n| extinct_title           = Disestablished\n| extinct_date            = \n| seat_type               = Region seat\n| seat                    = [[Landshut]]\n| area_total_km2          = 10329.87\n| population_footnotes    = {{#tag:ref| {{Population Germany|key=092|datref=QUELLE}} }}\n| population_total        = {{Population Germany|key=092 }}\n| population_as_of        = {{#time:j F Y|{{Population Germany|key=092|datref=STAND}} }} \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| website                 = [http://www.regierung.niederbayern.bayern.de regierung.niederbayern.bayern.de]\n}} \n[[File:Wappen Bezirk Niederbayern.svg|thumb|Coat of arms of Lower Bavaria]]\n'''Lower Bavaria''' ({{lang-de|Niederbayern}}) is one of the seven [[Regierungsbezirk|administrative region]]s of [[Bavaria]], [[Germany]], located in the east of the state.\n\n== Geography ==\nLower Bavaria is subdivided into two regions ({{lang|de|Planungsverband}}) \u2013 Landshut and Donau-Wald. Recent [[election]] results mark it as the most [[Conservatism|conservative]] part of Germany,{{cn|date=October 2018}} generally giving huge margins to the [[Christian Social Union of Bavaria|CSU]]. This part of Bavaria includes the [[Bavarian Forest]], a well-known tourist destination in Germany, and the [[Lower Bavarian Upland]].\n\n{{col-begin|width=auto}}\n{{col-break}}\n'''''Landkreise''<br>(districts)'''\n# [[Deggendorf (district)|Deggendorf]]\n# [[Dingolfing-Landau]]\n# [[Freyung-Grafenau]]\n# [[Kelheim (district)|Kelheim]]\n# [[Landshut (district)|Landshut]]\n# [[Passau (district)|Passau]]\n# [[Regen (district)|Regen]]\n# [[Rottal-Inn]]\n# [[Straubing-Bogen]]\n{{col-break|gap=2em}}\n'''''Kreisfreie St\u00e4dte''<br>(district-free towns)'''\n# [[Landshut]]\n# [[Passau]]\n# [[Straubing]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Population ==\n{{historical populations|cols=2\n| align=none | percentages = pagr\n| 1900 | 678,192\n| 1910 | 724,331\n| 1939 | 755,980\n| 1950 | 1,041,333\n| 1961 | 927,724\n| 1970 | 977,166\n| 1987 | 1,027,374\n| 2002 | 1,191,476\n| 2005 | 1,196,923\n| 2006 | 1,193,820\n| 2008 | 1,193,444\n| 2010 | 1,189,701\n|2018|1,238,528}}\n\n== Economy ==\nThe Gross domestic product (GDP) of the region was 48.5 billion \u20ac in 2018, accounting for 1.4% of German economic output. GDP per capita adjusted for purchasing power was 36,100 \u20ac or 120% of the EU27 average in the same year. The GDP per employee was 100% of the EU average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/2995521/10474907/1-05032020-AP-EN.pdf/81807e19-e4c8-2e53-c98a-933f5bf30f58|title=Regional GDP per capita ranged from 30% to 263% of the EU average in 2018|last=|first=|date=|website=Eurostat|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Main sights ==\n[[Image:2013 Weltenburg 18.jpg|thumb|right| [[Befreiungshalle]] with River [[Danube]]]]\nNext to the former ducal residences [[Landshut]] and [[Straubing]] and the baroque episcopal city of [[Passau]], the city of Kelheim with the [[Befreiungshalle]] and [[Weltenburg Abbey]] belong to the major tourist attractions. To the scenic attractions belong the River [[Danube]] including the Donaudurchbruch at Weltenburg and the [[Bavarian Forest]] with Mount [[Gro\u00dfer Arber]].\n\n== History ==\nThe Duchy of Lower Bavaria was created for the first time with the ''First Bavarian [[Partition (politics)|partition]]'' in 1255 under duke [[Henry XIII, Duke of Bavaria|Henry]] but there was no exact identity with the current territory. After the reunification in 1340, Bavaria was divided again in 1349, then in 1353 [[Bavaria-Straubing]] and [[Bavaria-Landshut]] were created in Lower Bavaria. In 1505 Bavaria was permanently reunited. For administrative purposes, Bavaria was split into ''Rent\u00e4mter'' (plural of ''{{ill|Rentamt|bar||de||es|Mayordom\u00eda}}''). Lower Bavaria consisted of the Rentamt Landshut and Rentamt Straubing.\n\nAfter the founding of the [[Kingdom of Bavaria]] following the dissolution of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] in 1805, the state was totally reorganized and, in 1808, divided into 15 administrative districts(German: Regierungsbezirke (singular Regierungsbezirk)), in Bavaria called Kreise (singular: Kreis). They were created in the fashion of the French departements, quite even in size and population, and named after their main rivers. In the following years, due to territorial changes (e. g. loss of [[German Tyrol|Tyrol]] [to [[Italy]] and [[Austria]]], addition of the [[Palatinate (region)|Palatinate]]), the number of districts was reduced to 8. One of these was the [[Unterdonaukreis]] (Lower Danube District). In 1837, King [[Ludwig I of Bavaria]] renamed the Kreise after historical territorial names and tribes. This also involved border changes or territorial swaps. Thus the Unterdonaukreis changed to Lower Bavaria. The district capital was moved from [[Passau]] to [[Landshut]] which was added from [[Isarkreis]].\n\nLower Bavaria and [[Upper Palatinate]] were consolidated in 1932 in one administrative district. In 1954 the two districts were restored again. In 1972 Lower Bavaria was reshaped when the rural districts covered were reshaped too.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.regierung.niederbayern.bayern.de Official website of government] {{in lang|de}}\n*[http://www.bezirk-niederbayern.de Official website of region] {{in lang|de|fr}}\n\n{{Regierungsbezirk (Bavaria)}}\n\n{{coord|48|31|N|12|09|E|type:adm2nd_source:itwiki|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Lower Bavaria| ]]\n[[Category:NUTS 2 statistical regions of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Government regions of Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Lower Bavaria\n| native_name             = Niederbayern\n| native_name_lang        = de\n| settlement_type         = [[Regierungsbezirk]]\n| image_map               = Locator map RB Niederbayern in Bavaria.svg\n| map_caption             = Map of [[Bavaria]] highlighting Lower Bavaria\n| coordinates             = \n| coor_pinpoint           = \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[Germany]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States of Germany|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Bavaria]]\n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n| extinct_title           = Disestablished\n| extinct_date            = \n| seat_type               = Region seat\n| seat                    = [[Landshut]]\n| area_total_km2          = 10329.87\n| population_footnotes    = {{#tag:ref| {{Population Germany|key=092|datref=QUELLE}} }}\n| population_total        = {{Population Germany|key=092 }}\n| population_as_of        = {{#time:j F Y|{{Population Germany|key=092|datref=STAND}} }} \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| website                 = [http://www.regierung.niederbayern.bayern.de regierung.niederbayern.bayern.de]\n}} \n[[File:Wappen Bezirk Niederbayern.svg|thumb|Coat of arms of Lower Bavaria]]\n'''Lower Bavaria''' ({{lang-de|Niederbayern}}) is one of the seven [[Regierungsbezirk|administrative region]]s of [[Bavaria]], [[Germany]], located in the east of the state.\n\n== Geography ==\nLower Bavaria is subdivided into two regions ({{lang|de|Planungsverband}}) \u2013 Landshut and Donau-Wald. Recent [[election]] results mark it as the most [[Conservatism|conservative]] part of Germany,{{cn|date=October 2018}} generally giving huge margins to the [[Christian Social Union of Bavaria|CSU]]. This part of Bavaria includes the [[Bavarian Forest]], a well-known tourist destination in Germany, and the [[Lower Bavarian Upland]].\n\n{{col-begin|width=auto}}\n{{col-break}}\n'''''Landkreise''<br>(districts)'''\n# [[Deggendorf (district)|Deggendorf]]\n# [[Dingolfing-Landau]]\n# [[Freyung-Grafenau]]\n# [[Kelheim (district)|Kelheim]]\n# [[Landshut (district)|Landshut]]\n# [[Passau (district)|Passau]]\n# [[Regen (district)|Regen]]\n# [[Rottal-Inn]]\n# [[Straubing-Bogen]]\n{{col-break|gap=2em}}\n'''''Kreisfreie St\u00e4dte''<br>(district-free towns)'''\n# [[Landshut]]\n# [[Passau]]\n# [[Straubing]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Population ==\n{{historical populations|cols=2\n| align=none | percentages = pagr\n| 1900 | 678,192\n| 1910 | 724,331\n| 1939 | 755,980\n| 1950 | 1,041,333\n| 1961 | 927,724\n| 1970 | 977,166\n| 1987 | 1,027,374\n| 2002 | 1,191,476\n| 2005 | 1,196,923\n| 2006 | 1,193,820\n| 2008 | 1,193,444\n| 2010 | 1,189,701\n|2018|1,238,528}}\n\n== Economy ==\nThe Gross domestic product (GDP) of the region was 48.5 billion \u20ac in 2018, accounting for 1.4% of German economic output. GDP per capita adjusted for purchasing power was 36,100 \u20ac or 120% of the EU27 average in the same year. The GDP per employee was 100% of the EU average.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/2995521/10474907/1-05032020-AP-EN.pdf/81807e19-e4c8-2e53-c98a-933f5bf30f58|title=Regional GDP per capita ranged from 30% to 263% of the EU average in 2018|last=|first=|date=|website=Eurostat|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Main sights ==\n[[Image:2013 Weltenburg 18.jpg|thumb|right| [[Befreiungshalle]] with River [[Danube]]]]\nNext to the former ducal residences [[Landshut]] and [[Straubing]] and the baroque episcopal city of [[Passau]], the city of Kelheim with the [[Befreiungshalle]] and [[Weltenburg Abbey]] belong to the major tourist attractions. To the scenic attractions belong the River [[Danube]] including the Donaudurchbruch at Weltenburg and the [[Bavarian Forest]] with Mount [[Gro\u00dfer Arber]].\n\n== History ==\nThe Duchy of Lower Bavaria was created for the first time with the ''First Bavarian [[Partition (politics)|partition]]'' in 1255 under duke [[Henry XIII, Duke of Bavaria|Henry]] but there was no exact identity with the current territory. After the reunification in 1340, Bavaria was divided again in 1349, then in 1353 [[Bavaria-Straubing]] and [[Bavaria-Landshut]] were created in Lower Bavaria. In 1505 Bavaria was permanently reunited. For administrative purposes, Bavaria was split into ''Rent\u00e4mter'' (plural of ''{{ill|Rentamt|bar||de||es|Mayordom\u00eda}}''). Lower Bavaria consisted of the Rentamt Landshut and Rentamt Straubing.\n\nAfter the founding of the [[Kingdom of Bavaria]] following the dissolution of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] in 1805, the state was totally reorganized and, in 1808, divided into 15 administrative districts(German: Regierungsbezirke (singular Regierungsbezirk)), in Bavaria called Kreise (singular: Kreis). They were created in the fashion of the French departements, quite even in size and population, and named after their main rivers. In the following years, due to territorial changes (e. g. loss of [[German Tyrol|Tyrol]] [to [[Italy]] and [[Austria]]], addition of the [[Palatinate (region)|Palatinate]]), the number of districts was reduced to 8. One of these was the [[Unterdonaukreis]] (Lower Danube District). In 1837, King [[Ludwig I of Bavaria]] renamed the Kreise after historical territorial names and tribes. This also involved border changes or territorial swaps. Thus the Unterdonaukreis changed to Lower Bavaria. The district capital was moved from [[Passau]] to [[Landshut]] which was added from [[Isarkreis]].\n\nLower Bavaria and [[Upper Palatinate]] were consolidated 1932 in one administrative district. In 1954 the two districts were restored again. In 1972 Lower Bavaria was reshaped when the rural districts covered were reshaped, too.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.regierung.niederbayern.bayern.de Official website of government] {{in lang|de}}\n*[http://www.bezirk-niederbayern.de Official website of region] {{in lang|de|fr}}\n\n{{Regierungsbezirk (Bavaria)}}\n\n{{coord|48|31|N|12|09|E|type:adm2nd_source:itwiki|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Lower Bavaria| ]]\n[[Category:NUTS 2 statistical regions of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Government regions of Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Chrism", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lower_Bavaria"}
{"title_page": "Lotus Tower", "text_new": "{{short description|Telecommunications tower in Colombo, Sri Lanka}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name = Lotus Tower\n| native_name = Nelum Kuluna<br>{{lang|si|\u0db1\u0dd9\u0dc5\u0dd4\u0db8\u0dca \u0d9a\u0dd4\u0dc5\u0dd4\u0dab}}<br>{{lang|ta|\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bcb\u0baa\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bae\u0bcd}}<br>Thaamarai Kopuram\n| native_name_lang = \n| image = ColomboSkyline - November 2017 (1).jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| caption = Colombo Skyline with Lotus Tower\n| map_type = Sri Lanka Colombo Central#Sri Lanka#Asia#Earth\n| map_alt = \n| map_caption = Location in Central Colombo\n| status = Completed\n| completion_date = 15 September 2019\n| building_type = Mixed use:<br>\n{{bulleted list |[[Digital Terrestrial Television]] [[ISDB]]-T| Telecommunications| Observation| Hospitality| Events| Tourist attraction| Retail}}\n| location = [[Colombo]], [[Sri Lanka]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|06|55|37|N|79|51|30|E|region:LK|display=inline,title}}\n| antenna_spire = {{convert|356|m|ft|1|abbr=on}}\n| roof = \n| top_floor = \n| floor_count = 13<br> <small>(6 in base, 7 in flower)</small>\n| elevator_count = 8\n| architect = \n| opened_date = 16  September 2019\n| website = http://www.lotustower.lk/\n}}\n[[File:Lotus tower.jpg|thumb|336x336px|Lotus Tower]]\n'''Lotus Tower''' ({{lang-si|\u0db1\u0dd9\u0dc5\u0dd4\u0db8\u0dca \u0d9a\u0dd4\u0dc5\u0dd4\u0dab}}; {{lang-ta|\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bcb\u0baa\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bae\u0bcd}}), also referred to as '''Colombo Lotus Tower''', is a tower of {{convert|356|m|ft|abbr=on}}, located in [[Colombo]], [[Sri Lanka]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skyscrapercenter.com/building/lotus-tower/13823|title=Lotus Tower - The Skyscraper Center|website=www.skyscrapercenter.com|access-date=2017-12-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trc.gov.lk/events/colombo-lotus-tower-minister-basil-rajapakse-lays-foundation-stone.html|title=Foundation stone laid for Lotus Tower|access-date=21 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130309111734/http://www.trc.gov.lk/events/colombo-lotus-tower-minister-basil-rajapakse-lays-foundation-stone.html#|archive-date=9 March 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It also reflects the symbolic landmark of Sri Lanka.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2019/09/15/news-features/symbolic-landmark-sri-lanka-lotus-tower-nelum-kuluna|title=Symbolic landmark of Sri Lanka: Lotus Tower (Nelum Kuluna)|date=2019-09-14|website=Sunday Observer|language=en|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref>  As of 16 September 2019, the tower is currently the tallest self-supported structure in South Asia. It is also the second tallest structure in South Asia after the guy-wire-supported [[INS Kattabomman]] in India. The tower is also the 11th tallest completed tower in Asia and it is also the 19th tallest tower in the world.<ref name=\":0\" /> It was first proposed to be built in the suburb of [[Peliyagoda]] but later the Government of Sri Lanka decided to shift the location.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sundaytimes.lk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=13917:colombo-to-get-350m-high-multifunctional-communication-tower-soon&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=547|title=Colombo to get 350&nbsp;m high multifunctional communication tower soon |publisher=Sunday Times |accessdate= 15 December 2011}}</ref> The [[Lotus (plant)|lotus]]-shaped tower will be used for communication, observation and other leisure facilities, with construction costing $104.3 million, funded by EXIM Bank of [[People's Republic of China]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://asiantribune.com/news/2010/11/10/sri-lankan-version-rs-11bn-eiffel-tower-mooted |title=Sri Lankan version of Rs. 11bn Eiffel tower mooted |publisher=Asian Tribune News |accessdate=10 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419025251/http://asiantribune.com/news/2010/11/10/sri-lankan-version-rs-11bn-eiffel-tower-mooted |archivedate=19 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It is visible throughout [[Colombo]], its suburbs and most major highways radiating from and around the city.\n\nThe tower was opened to the public on the 16 September 2019 by [[President (government title)|President]] [[Maithripala Sirisena]], seven years after the project commenced.\n\n[[File:Loving Lotus Tower.jpg|thumb|506x506px|Lotus Tower,South Asia's Tallest Tower]]\n\n== Location ==\nAfter an initial decision to construct the tower within the confines of a suburb of the country's economic capital city of [[Colombo]], Sri Lanka's government announced their plans to shift the location to the heart of the city. The tower's new location is on the waterfront of the [[Beira Lake]].\n\n== Construction ==\nWith the witness of the President of Telecommunications Regulatory Commission of Sri Lanka (TRCSL), the Secretary of the Sri Lanka Foreign Ministry, the Presidents of China National Electronics Importers and Exporters Corporation (CEIEC) and Aerospace Long March International Trade Co. Ltd (ALIT) signed the contract with the Director-General of TRCSL, Anusha Palpita, for the project on 3 January 2012.<ref>[http://www.ceiec.com/news/549 CEIEC Signed the Contract of Colombo Lotus Tower Project], CEIEC.com News. Retrieved 3 January 2012</ref>\n\nThe project commenced during the tenure of former President [[Mahinda Rajapakse]] and the construction began on 20 January 2012 following a foundation stone-laying ceremony. The site is located on the waterfront of [[Beira Lake]] and alongside a part of the D. R. Wijewardene Mawatha.<ref>[http://www.trc.gov.lk/press-room/events/248-colombo-lotus-tower-minister-basil-rajapakse-lays-foundation-stone.html Colombo Lotus Tower \u2013 Minister Basil Rajapakse Lays Foundation Stone], TRCSL Press. Retrieved 20 January 2012</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, the tower's construction crossed the {{convert|125|m|ft|abbr=on}} milestone and as of July 2015, the tower had reached {{convert|255|m|ft|abbr=on}}.\n\n== Design and function ==\nThe design of this building is inspired by the [[Nelumbo nucifera|Lotus]] flower. The lotus symbolizes purity within Sri Lankan culture and is also said to symbolize the country's flourishing development. The tower base is inspired by the lotus throne and will also be formed by two inverted [[trapezoidal]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The tower's color is planned to alternate between pink and light yellow by smooth transition- an effect achieved by coating the glass.\n\nThe tower is approximately {{convert|350|m|ft|abbr=on}} tall and covers {{convert|30,600|sqm|sqft|abbr=on}} of floor area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://akathy.com/moreartical.php?newsid=600&cat=srilanka&sel=current&subcat=2|title=Lotus Tower in Colombo|publisher=Akathy|accessdate=20 January 2012}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nLotus Tower's main revenue sources will be tourism and antenna leasing. It will function as a radio and television broadcasting antenna [[ISDB]]-T and proposed [[DVB-T2]] support structure for 50 television services, 35 FM Radio Stations and 20 telecommunication service providers,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=123392|title=Chinese contractor puts India at ease; Dispute over Colombo Lotus Tower|accessdate=29 April 2017|date=20 April 2015|publisher=The Island}}</ref> and will house a variety of tourist attractions {{citation needed|date=August 2015}}.\n\nThe tower has four entrances, with two being used as VIP (distinguished guests and state leaders) entrances. A telecommunications museum and restaurant are located on the ground floor. The tower podium consists of 6 floors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lankabusinessonline.com/lotus-tower-tallest-in-south-asia-to-open-today/|title=Lotus Tower, tallest in South Asia to open today|last=LBO|date=2019-09-16|website=Lanka Business Online|language=en-US|access-date=16 September 2019}}</ref> The first floor of the podium will accommodate a museum and two exhibition halls. The second floor will be utilised for several conference halls with seating space in excess of 500 people. Restaurants, supermarkets, and food courts will be situated on the third floor. A 1000-seat auditorium will be located on the fourth floor, which will also be used as a ballroom. The fifth floor will include luxury hotel rooms, large ballrooms, and the seventh floor will host an observation gallery. The landscaping is planned in the form of a large water park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.development.lk/news.php?news=1570|title=Tallest in South Asia|publisher=Development LK|accessdate=20  January 2012|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120728170552/http://www.development.lk/news.php?news=1570#|archive-date=28 July 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trc.gov.lk/press-room/events/243-colombo-lotus-tower-project-contract-signing-ceremony.html|title=Colombo Lotus Tower Project Contract Signing Ceremony|publisher=TRCSL Press |accessdate= 20 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lotus tower.png|thumb|left|Lotus Tower]]\n\n== Transport Hub ==\nThe [[Colombo Monorail]], which was a proposed monorail system in [[Colombo]], and the [[Bus rapid transport|BRT]] system were to converge at a common 'multi-modal hub' located in close proximity to the Lotus Tower, making the tower a major city center. The Monorail was canceled in 2016, and instead, a [[light rail]] will be constructed in Colombo.\n\n== Controversy ==\nDuring the opening ceremony which was held on 16 September 2019, Former President [[Maithripala Sirisena]] at a ceremonial speech mentioned and claimed an allegation on a scam regarding an advance of 2 billion rupees which was given to an approved company ALIT in 2012 by the then government, was later revealed in 2016 that such a company did not exist. However this was later proven to be false as ALIT was in fact the acronym of the Chinese state-owned Aerospace Long-March International Trade Co. ALIT denied receiving the payment claiming that the entire amount was paid to the China National Electronics Import & Export Corporation (CEIEC) as had ALIT left the project. It also noted that the TRC paid $15.6 million (2 billion rupees) into CEIEC's account in Exim Bank in October 2012, the same amount which Sirisena claims to have been \"misappropriated\" by ALIT.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economynext.com/china-firm-vanishes-with-billions-in-sri-lanka-lotus-tower-scam-24693/|title=China firm vanishes with billions in Sri Lanka Lotus Tower scam|date=2019-09-16|website=EconomyNext|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=China's ALIT rejects Sri Lanka leader's graft allegation |url=https://mobile.reuters.com/article/amp/idUSL3N26B3MI |website=www.reuters.com |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Nelum Pokuna Mahinda Rajapaksa Theatre]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Tallest structures in Sri Lanka}}\n{{Supertall}}\n{{2019 in Sri Lanka}}\n\n[[Category:Communication towers in Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:2019 establishments in Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Observation towers]]\n[[Category:Restaurant towers]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Colombo]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Telecommunications tower in Colombo, Sri Lanka}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name = Lotus Tower\n| native_name = Nelum Kuluna<br>{{lang|si|\u0db1\u0dd9\u0dc5\u0dd4\u0db8\u0dca \u0d9a\u0dd4\u0dc5\u0dd4\u0dab}}<br>{{lang|ta|\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bcb\u0baa\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bae\u0bcd}}<br>Thaamarai Kopuram\n| native_name_lang = \n| image = ColomboSkyline - November 2017 (1).jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| caption = Colombo Skyline with Lotus Tower\n| map_type = Sri Lanka Colombo Central#Sri Lanka#Asia#Earth\n| map_alt = \n| map_caption = Location in Central Colombo\n| status = Completed\n| completion_date = 15 September 2019\n| building_type = Mixed use:<br>\n{{bulleted list |[[Digital Terrestrial Television]] [[ISDB]]-T| Telecommunications| Observation| Hospitality| Events| Tourist attraction| Retail}}\n| location = [[Colombo]], [[Sri Lanka]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|06|55|37|N|79|51|30|E|region:LK|display=inline,title}}\n| antenna_spire = {{convert|356|m|ft|1|abbr=on}}\n| roof = \n| top_floor = \n| floor_count = 13<br> <small>(6 in base, 7 in flower)</small>\n| elevator_count = 8\n| architect = \n| opened_date = 16  September 2019\n| website = http://www.lotustower.lk/\n}}\n[[File:Lotus tower.jpg|thumb|336x336px|Lotus Tower]]\n'''Lotus Tower''' ({{lang-si|\u0db1\u0dd9\u0dc5\u0dd4\u0db8\u0dca \u0d9a\u0dd4\u0dc5\u0dd4\u0dab}}; {{lang-ta|\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0b95\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bcb\u0baa\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bae\u0bcd}}), also referred to as '''Colombo Lotus Tower''', is a tower of {{convert|356|m|ft|abbr=on}}, located in [[Colombo]], [[Sri Lanka]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skyscrapercenter.com/building/lotus-tower/13823|title=Lotus Tower - The Skyscraper Center|website=www.skyscrapercenter.com|access-date=2017-12-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trc.gov.lk/events/colombo-lotus-tower-minister-basil-rajapakse-lays-foundation-stone.html|title=Foundation stone laid for Lotus Tower|access-date=21 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130309111734/http://www.trc.gov.lk/events/colombo-lotus-tower-minister-basil-rajapakse-lays-foundation-stone.html#|archive-date=9 March 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It also reflects the symbolic landmark of Sri Lanka.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2019/09/15/news-features/symbolic-landmark-sri-lanka-lotus-tower-nelum-kuluna|title=Symbolic landmark of Sri Lanka: Lotus Tower (Nelum Kuluna)|date=2019-09-14|website=Sunday Observer|language=en|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref>  As of 16 September 2019, the tower is currently the tallest self-supported structure in South Asia. It is also the second tallest structure in South Asia after the guy-wire-supported [[INS Kattabomman]] in India. The tower is also the 11th tallest completed tower in Asia and it is also the 19th tallest tower in the world.<ref name=\":0\" /> It was first proposed to be built in the suburb of [[Peliyagoda]] but later the Government of Sri Lanka decided to shift the location.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sundaytimes.lk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=13917:colombo-to-get-350m-high-multifunctional-communication-tower-soon&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=547|title=Colombo to get 350&nbsp;m high multifunctional communication tower soon |publisher=Sunday Times |accessdate= 15 December 2011}}</ref> The [[Lotus (plant)|lotus]]-shaped tower will be used for communication, observation and other leisure facilities, with construction costing $104.3 million, funded by EXIM Bank of [[People's Republic of China]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://asiantribune.com/news/2010/11/10/sri-lankan-version-rs-11bn-eiffel-tower-mooted |title=Sri Lankan version of Rs. 11bn Eiffel tower mooted |publisher=Asian Tribune News |accessdate=10 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419025251/http://asiantribune.com/news/2010/11/10/sri-lankan-version-rs-11bn-eiffel-tower-mooted |archivedate=19 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It is visible throughout [[Colombo]], its suburbs and most major highways radiating from and around the city.\n\nThe tower was opened to the public on the 16 September 2019 by [[President (government title)|President]] [[Maithripala Sirisena]], seven years after the project commenced.\n\n[[File:Loving Lotus Tower.jpg|thumb|506x506px|Lotus Tower,South Asia's Tallest Tower]]\n\n== Location ==\nAfter an initial decision to construct the tower within the confines of a suburb of the country's economic capital city of [[Colombo]], Sri Lanka's government announced their plans to shift the location to the heart of the city. The tower's new location is on the waterfront of the [[Beira Lake]].\n\n== Construction ==\nWith the witness of the President of Telecommunications Regulatory Commission of Sri Lanka (TRCSL), the Secretary of the Sri Lanka Foreign Ministry, the Presidents of China National Electronics Importers and Exporters Corporation (CEIEC) and Aerospace Long March International Trade Co. Ltd (ALIT) signed the contract with the Director-General of TRCSL, Anusha Palpita, for the project on 3 January 2012.<ref>[http://www.ceiec.com/news/549 CEIEC Signed the Contract of Colombo Lotus Tower Project], CEIEC.com News. Retrieved 3 January 2012</ref>\n\nThe project commenced during the tenure of former President [[Mahinda Rajapakse]] and the construction began on 20 January 2012 following a foundation stone-laying ceremony. The site is located on the waterfront of [[Beira Lake]] and alongside a part of the D. R. Wijewardene Mawatha.<ref>[http://www.trc.gov.lk/press-room/events/248-colombo-lotus-tower-minister-basil-rajapakse-lays-foundation-stone.html Colombo Lotus Tower \u2013 Minister Basil Rajapakse Lays Foundation Stone], TRCSL Press. Retrieved 20 January 2012</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, the tower's construction crossed the {{convert|125|m|ft|abbr=on}} milestone and as of July 2015, the tower had reached {{convert|255|m|ft|abbr=on}}.\n\n== Design and function ==\nThe design of this building is inspired by the [[Nelumbo nucifera|Lotus]] flower. The lotus symbolizes purity within Sri Lankan culture and is also said to symbolize the country's flourishing development. The tower base is inspired by the lotus throne and will also be formed by two inverted [[trapezoidal]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The tower's color is planned to alternate between pink and light yellow by smooth transition- an effect achieved by coating the glass.\n\nThe tower is approximately {{convert|350|m|ft|abbr=on}} tall and covers {{convert|30,600|sqm|sqft|abbr=on}} of floor area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://akathy.com/moreartical.php?newsid=600&cat=srilanka&sel=current&subcat=2|title=Lotus Tower in Colombo|publisher=Akathy|accessdate=20 January 2012}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nLotus Tower's main revenue sources will be tourism and antenna leasing. It will function as a radio and television broadcasting antenna [[ISDB]]-T and proposed [[DVB-T2]] support structure for 50 television services, 35 FM Radio Stations and 20 telecommunication service providers,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=123392|title=Chinese contractor puts India at ease; Dispute over Colombo Lotus Tower|accessdate=29 April 2017|date=20 April 2015|publisher=The Island}}</ref> and will house a variety of tourist attractions {{citation needed|date=August 2015}}.\n\nThe tower has four entrances, with two being used as VIP (distinguished guests and state leaders) entrances. A telecommunications museum and restaurant are located on the ground floor. The tower podium consists of 6 floors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lankabusinessonline.com/lotus-tower-tallest-in-south-asia-to-open-today/|title=Lotus Tower, tallest in South Asia to open today|last=LBO|date=2019-09-16|website=Lanka Business Online|language=en-US|access-date=16 September 2019}}</ref> The first floor of the podium will accommodate a museum and two exhibition halls. The second floor will be utilised for several conference halls with seating space in excess of 500 people. Restaurants, supermarkets, and food courts will be situated on the third floor. A 1000-seat auditorium will be located on the fourth floor, which will also be used as a ballroom. The fifth floor will include luxury hotel rooms, large ballrooms, and the seventh floor will host an observation gallery. The landscaping is planned in the form of a large water park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.development.lk/news.php?news=1570|title=Tallest in South Asia|publisher=Development LK|accessdate=20  January 2012|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120728170552/http://www.development.lk/news.php?news=1570#|archive-date=28 July 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trc.gov.lk/press-room/events/243-colombo-lotus-tower-project-contract-signing-ceremony.html|title=Colombo Lotus Tower Project Contract Signing Ceremony|publisher=TRCSL Press |accessdate= 20 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lotus tower.png|thumb|left|Lotus Tower]]\n\n== Transport Hub ==\nThe [[Colombo Monorail]], which was a proposed monorail system in [[Colombo]], and the [[Bus rapid transport|BRT]] system were to converge at a common 'multi-modal hub' located in close proximity to the Lotus Tower, making the tower a major city center. The Monorail was canceled in 2016, and instead, a [[light rail]] will be constructed in Colombo.\n\n== Controversy ==\nDuring the opening ceremony which was held on 16 September 2019, incumbent President [[Maithripala Sirisena]] at a ceremonial speech mentioned and claimed an allegation on a scam regarding an advance of 2 billion rupees which was given to an approved company ALIT in 2012 by the then government, was later revealed in 2016 that such a company did not exist. However this was later proven to be false as ALIT was in fact the acronym of the Chinese state-owned Aerospace Long-March International Trade Co. ALIT denied receiving the payment claiming that the entire amount was paid to the China National Electronics Import & Export Corporation (CEIEC) as had ALIT left the project. It also noted that the TRC paid $15.6 million (2 billion rupees) into CEIEC's account in Exim Bank in October 2012, the same amount which Sirisena claims to have been \"misappropriated\" by ALIT.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economynext.com/china-firm-vanishes-with-billions-in-sri-lanka-lotus-tower-scam-24693/|title=China firm vanishes with billions in Sri Lanka Lotus Tower scam|date=2019-09-16|website=EconomyNext|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=China's ALIT rejects Sri Lanka leader's graft allegation |url=https://mobile.reuters.com/article/amp/idUSL3N26B3MI |website=www.reuters.com |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Nelum Pokuna Mahinda Rajapaksa Theatre]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Tallest structures in Sri Lanka}}\n{{Supertall}}\n{{2019 in Sri Lanka}}\n\n[[Category:Communication towers in Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:2019 establishments in Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Observation towers]]\n[[Category:Restaurant towers]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Colombo]]\n", "name_user": "Sanjayts1997", "label": "safe", "comment": "Maithripala siresena is the former president , gotabaya rajapaksa is the incumbent president of sri lanka", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lotus_Tower"}
{"title_page": "Choi Jong-hoon", "text_new": "{{Korean name|Choi}}\n{{Infobox musical artist|\n| name            = Choi Jong-hoon\n| image           = Choi Jong-hoon.png\n| image_upright   = 1.25\n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1990|3|7}}\n| birth_place     = [[Seoul]], South Korea\n| origin          = \n| background      = solo_singer\n| genre           = {{flatlist|\n* [[rock music|Rock]]\n* [[pop music|pop]]\n* [[contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n}}\n| instrument      = Guitar, keyboard, vocals\n| years_active    = 2007\u20132019\n| label           = {{flatlist|\n* [[FNC Entertainment|FNC]]\n* AI\n* [[Warner Music Group|Warner Japan]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = [[F.T. Island]], F.T. Triple\n| url             = {{url|fncent.com/ftisland/}}\n| module          = {{Infobox Korean name|child=yes\n| title  = [[Korean name]]\n| hangul = {{linktext|\ucd5c|\uc885\ud6c8}}\n| hanja  = {{linktext|\u5d14|\u9418|\u8a13}}\n| rr     = Choe Jong-hun\n| mr     = Ch'oe Chonghun\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''Choi Jong-hoon''' ({{Korean|hangul=\ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8}}, {{IPA-ko|t\u0255\u02b0\u00f8 d\u0291o\u014b\u0266u\u02d0n|pron}}; born March 7, 1990) is a former South Korean musician and actor. He served as the leader, guitarist, and keyboardist of rock band [[F.T. Island]] from its debut in 2007 until his retirement from the entertainment industry in 2019.\n\nOn March 14, 2019, Choi retired from the entertainment industry, amidst allegations of being involved in bribery and sharing of illicit sex videos and pictures, a part of the [[Jung Joon-young KakaoTalk chatrooms]], first revealed in the [[Burning Sun scandal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/seungri-reportedly-among-recipients-of-sex-videos-sent-by-singer-jung-joon|title=K-pop scandal: Two more artists, Choi Jong-hoon and Junhyung, quit show business|newspaper=[[The Straits Times]]|accessdate=March 14, 2019|date=March 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Agency kicks out F.T. Island member |url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/art/2019/03/732_265841.html |work=Korea Times |first=Lee|last=Gyu-lee|date=22 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref> On November 29, 2019, Choi was found guilty and sentenced to five years in prison.<ref>{{cite news|title=K-pop stars Jung Joon-young and Choi Jong-hoon sentenced for rape|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-50596943|website=[[BBC]]|date=November 29, 2019|accessdate=November 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=K-pop stars Jung Joon-young and Choi Jong-hoon sentenced to prison for rape|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-29/k-pop-stars-jung-joon-young-choi-jong-hoon-sentenced-prison-rape/11752066|website=[[ABC News]]|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nChoi Jong-hoon was born in [[Seoul]], South Korea on March 7, 1990,<ref name=\"Russell2014\">{{cite book|author=Mark Russell|title=K-Pop Now!: The Korean Music Revolution|page=60|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=etDZAwAAQBAJ|date=29 April 2014|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|isbn=978-1-4629-1411-1}}</ref> according to the [[solar calendar]], and February 6 according to the [[lunar calendar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ftisland.jp/ft2009/contents/profile.php|title=Profile|publisher=FTISLAND|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304151542/http://www.ftisland.jp/ft2009/contents/profile.php|archivedate=2009-03-04|language=Japanese}}</ref> He attended the Shindongshin Middle Information Industry High School. During his high school years, he was accepted into the FNC Music talent agency, which later formed the band [[F.T. Island]] with Jong-hoon as its leader and guitarist.\n\nChoi attended [[University of Suwon]], majoring in [[digital audio|digital music]] alongside former band member Oh Won Bin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200903021204041002&search=title&searchstring=%C3%D6%C1%BE%C8%C6|script-title=ko:\uc0c8\ub0b4\uae30 \uc624\uc6d0\ube48-\ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8, \ub098\ub780\ud788 \uc804\uc790\ub514\uc9c0\ud138\uc74c\uc545\ud559\uacfc \uc785\ud559!|publisher=Newsen|date=2009-03-02|accessdate=2014-04-13|language=Korean}}</ref>\n\n==Music career==\n{{Main|F.T. Island}}\nIn January 2009, members Choi Jong-hoon, Choi Minhwan, and Lee Jaejin were put into the sub group \"A3\". This group debuted at the 2009 [[New Year]] concert \"My First Dream\" held at the [[JCB Hall]] in Tokyo, Japan on January 2, 2009. Choi performed as the guitarist and a sub-vocalist. The group's name was \"A3\" due to each of the three members having type A blood. This group was formed to help take up some singing time during their concerts, so that lead singer, [[Lee Hong-gi]], would not overstrain his voice.<ref>{{cite news |title=[\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5] FT\uc544\uc77c\ub79c\ub4dc \uce21 \"\ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8 '\uc815\uae00' \ud6c4\ubc1c\ub300 \ud569\ub958, 2\uc6d4 \ucd9c\uad6d\"|url=https://www.entertain.naver.com/read?oid=109&aid=0003467768 |work=entertain.naver.com |language=ko}}</ref>\n\n==Television and acting==\nChoi began making cameos and guest appearances on many television series starting in 2008. Together with Song Seung-hyun, he starred in ''Style Wave'' in December 2009 and January 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www3.mb.com.ph/node/244772|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100301052143/http://www.mb.com.ph/node/244772|archivedate=2010-03-01|title=FTIsland brings K-pop mania anew in Manila|date=2010-02-22|publisher=Manila Bulletin}}</ref> In this show, stars discuss major style trends and dress a shopper according to a chosen style theme.\n\nChoi participated in episode 15 of [[Seoul Broadcasting System]]'s ''Idol Maknae Rebellion'' ({{Korean|hangul=\uc544\uc774\ub3cc \ub9c9\ub0b4\ubc18\ub780\uc2dc\ub300|labels=no}}) with fellow band member Seung-hyun, who was a cast member of the show; the episode aired on February 15, 2010. He made his acting debut as a supporting character in the film ''[[You're My Pet (film)|You're My Pet]]'' (2011) starring actors [[Jang Keun-suk]] and [[Kim Ha-neul]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Choi|first1=Min-ji|script-title=ko:FT \uc544\uc77c\ub79c\ub4dc \ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8, \uc7a5\uadfc\uc11d-\uae40\ud558\ub298 \uc8fc\uc5f0 '\ub108\ub294 \ud3ab' \ucd9c\uc5f0 \ud655\uc815|url=http://tvdaily.asiae.co.kr/read.php3?aid=1297820957131766010|website=TV Daily|accessdate=March 16, 2019|language=Korean|date=February 16, 2011}}</ref> Based on the Japanese manga ''[[Tramps Like Us]]'', Choi plays the younger brother of Kim's character. The film centers around a woman living with her human pet.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gil|first1=Hye-seong|title=ko:'\ubc30\uc6b0 \ub370\ubdd4' \ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8 \"\ucd9c\uc5f0 \uc815\ud574\uc84c\uc744 \ub54c \ub5a8\uc5c8\ub2e4\"|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/stview.php?no=2011030408322740656|website=Starnews|publisher=MT Media Group|accessdate=March 16, 2019|language=Korean|date=March 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, Choi joined the second season of tvN's ''The Romantic & Idol''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soompi.com/2012/12/31/ft-islands-choi-jong-hoon-dated-two-celebrities-since-his-debut/#.U0ri7vl_tqU|title=FT Island's Choi Jong-hoon Dated Two Celebrities Since His Debut|publisher=[[Soompi]]|date=2012-12-31|accessdate=2014-04-13}}</ref>\n\nChoi was cast as the lead character Park Shi-hyun in the web drama ''Prince's Prince'' (2015). [[Seo Yu-na]] of girl group [[AOA (band)|AOA]], who plays his onscreen younger sister Yu-na, [[Lim Yoon-ho]] as Lee Mong-ryong, also played co-leads. Based on the [[webtoon]] of the same name, the series revolves around Shi-hyun's sister and her immersion into video games.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yoon|first1=So-hee|script-title=ko:\uc6f9\ub4dc\ub77c\ub9c8 '\ud504\ub9b0\uc2a4\uc758 \uc655\uc790', FT\uc544\uc77c\ub79c\ub4dc \ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8 AOA \uc720\ub098 \uce90\uc2a4\ud305|url=http://tenasia.hankyung.com/archives/437085|website=10asia|publisher=Korea Entertainment Media|accessdate=March 16, 2019|language=Korean|date=February 6, 2015}}</ref> As a first-time lead role, Choi remarked during a press conference prior to filming, \"I previously did a bit of acting, but I should carefully and cautiously undertake this role\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Woo-in|script-title=ko:'\uc15c\ub85dK' \ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8 \"\uc5f0\uae30\uc790\ub85c\ub3c4 \uc0c8\ucd9c\ubc1c, \ub450\ub9c8\ub9ac \ud1a0\ub07c \uc7a1\uaca0\ub2e4\"|url=https://www.tvreport.co.kr/?c=news&m=newsview&idx=653375|website=TVreport|accessdate=March 16, 2019|language=Korean|date=February 9, 2015}}</ref> He also starred in the drama ''Heroes'' and ''Unexpected Heroes'' (2017).<ref>{{cite news |title=[\ud604\uc7a5] \u2018\ub73b\ubc16\uc758 \ud788\uc5b4\ub85c\uc988\u2019 \ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8-\uc774\ubbfc\ud601 \u201c\uae40\uc18c\ud61c, \uc2e4\uc81c\ub85c \ubcf4\ub2c8 \ub354 \ub7ec\ube14\ub9ac\u201d |url=https://www.sedaily.com/NewsView/1OOU93FZUL |work=\uc11c\uc6b8\uacbd\uc81c |date=13 December 2017 |language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u2018\ud504\ub9b0\uc2a4\uc758 \uc655\uc790\u2019 \ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8, \uc774\ub7f0 \uac8c \u2018\ub9cc\ucc22\ub0a8\u2019\uc758 \uc815\uc11d |url=https://mnews.sbs.co.kr/news/endPage.do?newsId=N1003004697 |work=SBS NEWS |date=2 June 2015 |language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=\uc7ac\ubc30\ud3ec\uae08\uc9c0> |first1=<\u24d2 \u201c\ud150\uc544\uc2dc\uc544\u201d \ubb34\ub2e8\uc804\uc7ac |title={{!}} '\ub73b\ubc16\uc758 \ud788\uc5b4\ub85c\uc988' \ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8, \ud654\ub824\ud55c \uc561\uc158\uc5d0 \uc9c1\uc9c4 \uace0\ubc31\uae4c\uc9c0 '\ub9e4\ub825 \ubc29\ucd9c'\ud150\uc544\uc2dc\uc544 |url=http://tenasia.hankyung.com/archives/1380151#_enliple |work=\ud150\uc544\uc2dc\uc544 |date=27 December 2017 |language=ko-KR}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\nWith fellow band member [[Song Seung-hyun]], Choi modeled at the 2009 Autumn Seoul Fashion Week on October 17, 2009 for Lee Ju Young, the designer of the \"Resurrection\" collection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200910171706051010&search=title&searchstring=%C3%D6%C1%BE%C8%C6|script-title=ko:\ud328\uc158\uc1fc \uc624\ub978 \ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8, \ub2f9\ub2f9\ud558\uac8c \uac77\uae30~|publisher=Newsen|date=2009-10-17|accessdate=2014-04-13|language=Korean}}</ref> On June 29, 2009, he was featured with Core Contents Media's soloist Hong Jin Young as one of the main characters in her [[music video]] \"Love Battery\". In August he participated in episode 19 of MNet Scandal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soompi.com/2009/09/15/mnet-scandal-featuring-ft-island-jong-hoon-slammed-for-too-much-skinship/#.U0rhR_l_tqU|title=MNet Scandal Featuring FT Island Jong-hoon Slammed For Too Much Skinship|date=2009-09-15|publisher=[[Soompi]]|accessdate=2014-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy and retirement==\n{{main|Burning Sun scandal}}\n\n===Departure===\nIn March 2019, Choi was revealed to be a member of an online group chat that shared sexually explicit videos of women filmed without their knowledge or consent, together with celebrities [[Lee Jong Hyun ]] and [[Jung Joon-young]]. He was also reported to have bribed the police in order to prevent newspapers from covering a drunk driving incident he was involved in 2016. Subsequently, his agency announced that he will be leaving [[F.T. Island]] and retiring from the entertainment industry.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/k-pop-rocked-by-new-scandal-fans-ask-ft-islands-leader-choi-jong-hoon-to|title=K-pop rocked by new scandal, fans ask FT Island's leader Choi Jong-hoon to quit|work=The Strait Times|date= March 13, 2019|accessdate=March 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, police booked Choi for illegally filming women without their consent, distributing a total of six videos, and bribery to cover up his drunk-driving incident.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/seungri-charged-over-embezzlement|title=Seungri charged over embezzlement|work=The Strait Times|date=April 2, 2019|accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.eonline.com/ap/news/1028847/choi-jong-hoon-is-booked-with-additional-charges-of-filming-illicit-videos|title=Choi Jong-Hoon Booked With Additional Charges of Filming Illicit Videos|work=E Online|date=April 1, 2019|accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref> On April 11, 2019, Choi admitted to spreading hidden camera photos taken without consent and also filming illegal hidden camera footage. He was charged with one count of sharing personally taken illegal footage and five counts of sharing footage from other sources.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2019/04/11/roy-kim-eddy-kim-choi-jong-hoon-admit-sharing-illegally-taken-photos|title=Roy Kim, Eddy Kim & Choi Jong Hoon admit to sharing illegally taken photos|work=SBS Australia|date=April 11, 2019|accessdate=April 11, 2019}}</ref> \n\n===Arrest===\nOn April 19, 2019, a woman came forward to [[SBS funE]], claiming that five men including Choi, had raped her after she was intoxicated in March 2016, and then shared the footage in a group chat. Choi denied the allegation, but admitted that he and the woman were together on that day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20190419000435|title=Jung Joon-young, Choi Jong-hoon accused of taking part in gang rape: report|work=[[The Korea Herald]]|first=Ju-young|last=Park|date=April 19, 2019|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5] '\uc9d1\ub2e8 \uc131\ud3ed\ud589 \uc758\ud639' \ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8 \ucd9c\uad6d\uae08\uc9c0...\ub0b4\uc8fc \uc18c\ud658|url=https://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=102&oid=052&aid=0001284958|date=April 25, 2019|work=[[YTN]]|accessdate=April 26, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> On May 10, 2019, Choi was arrested on the gang rape allegations and was indicted on charge of taking part in a gang rape in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Singer Choi Jong-hoon Arrested for Alleged Gang Rape|url=http://world.kbs.co.kr/service/news_view.htm?lang=e&Seq_Code=145075|date=May 10, 2019|work=[[KBS World]]|accessdate=May 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Boy Band Member Arrested for Rape|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2019/05/10/2019051001325.html|date=May 10, 2019|work=[[The Chosun Ilbo]]|first=Seung-jae|last=Kim|accessdate=May 10, 2019}}</ref> On November 29, 2019, Choi was sentenced to five years in prison for gang raping drunk unconscious women.<ref>{{cite news|title=K-pop stars Jung Joon-young and Choi Jong-hoon sentenced for rape|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-50596943|website=[[BBC]]|date=November 29, 2019|accessdate=November 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=K-pop stars Jung Joon-young and Choi Jong-hoon sentenced to prison for rape|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-29/k-pop-stars-jung-joon-young-choi-jong-hoon-sentenced-prison-rape/11752066|website=[[ABC News]]|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television series===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 700px;\"\n! Year !! Network !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2008 || [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]] ||''[[On Air (TV series)|On Air]]'' || Himself || Cameo (Ep. 1)\n|-\n| 2009 || [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]] || ''[[Style (TV series)|Style]]'' || Himself || Cameo (Ep. 6)\n|-\n| 2012\u20132013 || [[tvN]] || ''Romantic & Idol Season 2'' || Himself || Cast member\n|-\n| 2013\u20132014 || [[TVN (South Korea)|tvN]] || ''[[Cheongdam-dong 111]]'' || Himself || Reality show\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2015 ||[[Naver| Naver TV cast]], [[KBS2]] || ''Prince's Prince'' || Park Shi-hyun  || Lead role, web drama\n|-\n| [[JTBC]] || ''Heroes'' || Choi Hee-yeol || Lead role\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2017 || [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]] || ''Law of the Jungle'' || Himself || Sumatra Guest (Ep. 261 - 264)\n|-\n|Naver TV Cast || ''Unexpected Heroes'' || Min Su-ho || Web-drama\n|-\n|2018 || [[Maeil Broadcasting Network|MBN]] || ''[[Real Life Men and Women]]'' || Himself || Cast member\n|}\n\n===Film===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 700px;\"\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[You're My Pet (film)|You're My Pet]]'' || Ji Eun-soo || Supporting role\n|}\n\n==Discography==\n{{See also|F.T. Island discography}}\n\n===Guest appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20em;\"|Title\n! scope=\"col\"|Year\n! scope=\"col\"|Release\n! scope=\"col\"|{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|\"Wish Ver.2\" ({{Korean|hangul=\uc18c\ub9dd Ver.2|rr=Somang Ver.2|labels=no}})\n| 2009\n| ''Errand''\n| \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Choi Jong-hoon}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n \n{{F.T. Island}}\n{{Mnet Media}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Choi, Jong-hoon}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:FNC Entertainment artists]]\n[[Category:South Korean keyboardists]]\n[[Category:South Korean male idols]]\n[[Category:South Korean pop rock singers]]\n[[Category:F.T. Island members]]\n[[Category:South Korean rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:South Korean criminals]]\n[[Category:South Korean rapists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Korean name|Choi}}\n{{Infobox musical artist|\n| name            = Choi Jong-hoon\n| image           = Choi Jong-hoon.png\n| image_upright   = 1.25\n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1990|3|7}}\n| birth_place     = [[Seoul]], South Korea\n| origin          = \n| background      = solo_singer\n| genre           = {{flatlist|\n* [[rock music|Rock]]\n* [[pop music|pop]]\n* [[contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n}}\n| instrument      = Guitar, keyboard, vocals\n| years_active    = 2007\u20132019\n| label           = {{flatlist|\n* [[FNC Entertainment|FNC]]\n* AI\n* [[Warner Music Group|Warner Japan]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = [[F.T. Island]], F.T. Triple\n| url             = {{url|fncent.com/ftisland/}}\n| module          = {{Infobox Korean name|child=yes\n| title  = [[Korean name]]\n| hangul = {{linktext|\ucd5c|\uc885\ud6c8}}\n| hanja  = {{linktext|\u5d14|\u9418|\u8a13}}\n| rr     = Choe Jong-hun\n| mr     = Ch'oe Chonghun\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''Choi Jong-hoon''' ({{Korean|hangul=\ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8}}, {{IPA-ko|t\u0255\u02b0\u00f8 d\u0291o\u014b\u0266u\u02d0n|pron}}; born March 7, 1990) is a former South Korean musician and actor. He served as the leader, guitarist, and keyboardist of rock band [[F.T. Island]] from its debut in 2007 until his retirement from the entertainment industry in 2019.\n\nOn March 14, 2019, Choi retired from the entertainment industry, amidst allegations of being involved in bribery and sharing of illicit sex videos and pictures, a part of the [[Jung Joon-young KakaoTalk chatrooms]], first revealed in the [[Burning Sun scandal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/seungri-reportedly-among-recipients-of-sex-videos-sent-by-singer-jung-joon|title=K-pop scandal: Two more artists, Choi Jong-hoon and Junhyung, quit show business|newspaper=[[The Straits Times]]|accessdate=March 14, 2019|date=March 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Agency kicks out F.T. Island member |url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/art/2019/03/732_265841.html |work=Korea Times |first=Lee|last=Gyu-lee|date=22 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref> On November 29, 2019, Choi was found guilty and sentenced to five years in prison.<ref>{{cite news|title=K-pop stars Jung Joon-young and Choi Jong-hoon sentenced for rape|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-50596943|website=[[BBC]]|date=November 29, 2019|accessdate=November 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=K-pop stars Jung Joon-young and Choi Jong-hoon sentenced to prison for rape|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-29/k-pop-stars-jung-joon-young-choi-jong-hoon-sentenced-prison-rape/11752066|website=[[ABC News]]|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nChoi Jong-hoon was born in [[Seoul]], South Korea on March 7, 1990,<ref name=\"Russell2014\">{{cite book|author=Mark Russell|title=K-Pop Now!: The Korean Music Revolution|page=60|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=etDZAwAAQBAJ|date=29 April 2014|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|isbn=978-1-4629-1411-1}}</ref> according to the [[solar calendar]], and February 6 according to the [[lunar calendar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ftisland.jp/ft2009/contents/profile.php|title=Profile|publisher=FTISLAND|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304151542/http://www.ftisland.jp/ft2009/contents/profile.php|archivedate=2009-03-04|language=Japanese}}</ref> He attended the Shindongshin Middle Information Industry High School. During his high school years, he was accepted into the FNC Music talent agency, which later formed the band [[F.T. Island]] with Jong-hoon as its leader and guitarist.\n\nChoi attended [[University of Suwon]], majoring in [[digital audio|digital music]] alongside former band member Oh Won Bin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200903021204041002&search=title&searchstring=%C3%D6%C1%BE%C8%C6|script-title=ko:\uc0c8\ub0b4\uae30 \uc624\uc6d0\ube48-\ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8, \ub098\ub780\ud788 \uc804\uc790\ub514\uc9c0\ud138\uc74c\uc545\ud559\uacfc \uc785\ud559!|publisher=Newsen|date=2009-03-02|accessdate=2014-04-13|language=Korean}}</ref>\n\n==Music career==\n{{Main|F.T. Island}}\nIn January 2009, members Choi Jong-hoon, Choi Minhwan, and Lee Jaejin were put into the sub group \"A3\". This group debuted at the 2009 [[New Year]] concert \"My First Dream\" held at the [[JCB Hall]] in Tokyo, Japan on January 2, 2009. Choi performed as the guitarist and a sub-vocalist. The group's name was \"A3\" due to each of the three members having type A blood. This group was formed to help take up some singing time during their concerts, so that lead singer, [[Lee Hong-gi]], would not overstrain his voice.<ref>{{cite news |title=[\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5] FT\uc544\uc77c\ub79c\ub4dc \uce21 \"\ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8 '\uc815\uae00' \ud6c4\ubc1c\ub300 \ud569\ub958, 2\uc6d4 \ucd9c\uad6d\"|url=https://www.entertain.naver.com/read?oid=109&aid=0003467768 |work=entertain.naver.com |language=ko}}</ref>\n\n==Television and acting==\nChoi began making cameos and guest appearances on many television series starting in 2008. Together with Song Seung-hyun, he starred in ''Style Wave'' in December 2009 and January 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www3.mb.com.ph/node/244772|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100301052143/http://www.mb.com.ph/node/244772|archivedate=2010-03-01|title=FTIsland brings K-pop mania anew in Manila|date=2010-02-22|publisher=Manila Bulletin}}</ref> In this show, stars discuss major style trends and dress a shopper according to a chosen style theme.\n\nChoi participated in episode 15 of [[Seoul Broadcasting System]]'s ''Idol Maknae Rebellion'' ({{Korean|hangul=\uc544\uc774\ub3cc \ub9c9\ub0b4\ubc18\ub780\uc2dc\ub300|labels=no}}) with fellow band member Seung-hyun, who was a cast member of the show; the episode aired on February 15, 2010. He made his acting debut as a supporting character in the film ''[[You're My Pet (film)|You're My Pet]]'' (2011) starring actors [[Jang Keun-suk]] and [[Kim Ha-neul]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Choi|first1=Min-ji|script-title=ko:FT \uc544\uc77c\ub79c\ub4dc \ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8, \uc7a5\uadfc\uc11d-\uae40\ud558\ub298 \uc8fc\uc5f0 '\ub108\ub294 \ud3ab' \ucd9c\uc5f0 \ud655\uc815|url=http://tvdaily.asiae.co.kr/read.php3?aid=1297820957131766010|website=TV Daily|accessdate=March 16, 2019|language=Korean|date=February 16, 2011}}</ref> Based on the Japanese manga ''[[Tramps Like Us]]'', Choi plays the younger brother of Kim's character. The film centers around a woman living with her human pet.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gil|first1=Hye-seong|title=ko:'\ubc30\uc6b0 \ub370\ubdd4' \ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8 \"\ucd9c\uc5f0 \uc815\ud574\uc84c\uc744 \ub54c \ub5a8\uc5c8\ub2e4\"|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/stview.php?no=2011030408322740656|website=Starnews|publisher=MT Media Group|accessdate=March 16, 2019|language=Korean|date=March 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, Choi joined the second season of tvN's ''The Romantic & Idol''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soompi.com/2012/12/31/ft-islands-choi-jong-hoon-dated-two-celebrities-since-his-debut/#.U0ri7vl_tqU|title=FT Island's Choi Jong-hoon Dated Two Celebrities Since His Debut|publisher=[[Soompi]]|date=2012-12-31|accessdate=2014-04-13}}</ref>\n\nChoi was cast as the lead character Park Shi-hyun in the web drama ''Prince's Prince'' (2015). [[Seo Yu-na]] of girl group [[AOA (band)|AOA]], who plays his onscreen younger sister Yu-na, [[Lim Yoon-ho]] as Lee Mong-ryong, also played co-leads. Based on the [[webtoon]] of the same name, the series revolves around Shi-hyun's sister and her immersion into video games.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yoon|first1=So-hee|script-title=ko:\uc6f9\ub4dc\ub77c\ub9c8 '\ud504\ub9b0\uc2a4\uc758 \uc655\uc790', FT\uc544\uc77c\ub79c\ub4dc \ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8 AOA \uc720\ub098 \uce90\uc2a4\ud305|url=http://tenasia.hankyung.com/archives/437085|website=10asia|publisher=Korea Entertainment Media|accessdate=March 16, 2019|language=Korean|date=February 6, 2015}}</ref> As a first-time lead role, Choi remarked during a press conference prior to filming, \"I previously did a bit of acting, but I should carefully and cautiously undertake this role\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Woo-in|script-title=ko:'\uc15c\ub85dK' \ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8 \"\uc5f0\uae30\uc790\ub85c\ub3c4 \uc0c8\ucd9c\ubc1c, \ub450\ub9c8\ub9ac \ud1a0\ub07c \uc7a1\uaca0\ub2e4\"|url=https://www.tvreport.co.kr/?c=news&m=newsview&idx=653375|website=TVreport|accessdate=March 16, 2019|language=Korean|date=February 9, 2015}}</ref> He also starred in the drama ''Heroes'' and ''Unexpected Heroes'' (2017).<ref>{{cite news |title=[\ud604\uc7a5] \u2018\ub73b\ubc16\uc758 \ud788\uc5b4\ub85c\uc988\u2019 \ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8-\uc774\ubbfc\ud601 \u201c\uae40\uc18c\ud61c, \uc2e4\uc81c\ub85c \ubcf4\ub2c8 \ub354 \ub7ec\ube14\ub9ac\u201d |url=https://www.sedaily.com/NewsView/1OOU93FZUL |work=\uc11c\uc6b8\uacbd\uc81c |date=13 December 2017 |language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=\u2018\ud504\ub9b0\uc2a4\uc758 \uc655\uc790\u2019 \ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8, \uc774\ub7f0 \uac8c \u2018\ub9cc\ucc22\ub0a8\u2019\uc758 \uc815\uc11d |url=https://mnews.sbs.co.kr/news/endPage.do?newsId=N1003004697 |work=SBS NEWS |date=2 June 2015 |language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=\uc7ac\ubc30\ud3ec\uae08\uc9c0> |first1=<\u24d2 \u201c\ud150\uc544\uc2dc\uc544\u201d \ubb34\ub2e8\uc804\uc7ac |title={{!}} '\ub73b\ubc16\uc758 \ud788\uc5b4\ub85c\uc988' \ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8, \ud654\ub824\ud55c \uc561\uc158\uc5d0 \uc9c1\uc9c4 \uace0\ubc31\uae4c\uc9c0 '\ub9e4\ub825 \ubc29\ucd9c'\ud150\uc544\uc2dc\uc544 |url=http://tenasia.hankyung.com/archives/1380151#_enliple |work=\ud150\uc544\uc2dc\uc544 |date=27 December 2017 |language=ko-KR}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\nWith fellow band member [[Song Seung-hyun]], Choi modeled at the 2009 Autumn Seoul Fashion Week on October 17, 2009 for Lee Ju Young, the designer of the \"Resurrection\" collection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=200910171706051010&search=title&searchstring=%C3%D6%C1%BE%C8%C6|script-title=ko:\ud328\uc158\uc1fc \uc624\ub978 \ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8, \ub2f9\ub2f9\ud558\uac8c \uac77\uae30~|publisher=Newsen|date=2009-10-17|accessdate=2014-04-13|language=Korean}}</ref> On June 29, 2009, he was featured with Core Contents Media's soloist Hong Jin Young as one of the main characters in her [[music video]] \"Love Battery\". In August he participated in episode 19 of MNet Scandal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soompi.com/2009/09/15/mnet-scandal-featuring-ft-island-jong-hoon-slammed-for-too-much-skinship/#.U0rhR_l_tqU|title=MNet Scandal Featuring FT Island Jong-hoon Slammed For Too Much Skinship|date=2009-09-15|publisher=[[Soompi]]|accessdate=2014-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy and retirement==\n{{main|Burning Sun scandal}}\n\n===Departure===\nIn March 2019, Choi was revealed to be a member of an online group chat that shared sexually explicit videos of women filmed without their knowledge or consent, together with celebrities [[Lee Jong Hyun ]] and [[Jung Joon-young]]. He was also reported to have bribed the police in order to prevent newspapers from covering a drunk driving incident he was involved in 2016. Subsequently, his agency announced that he will be leaving [[F.T. Island]] and retiring from the entertainment industry.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/k-pop-rocked-by-new-scandal-fans-ask-ft-islands-leader-choi-jong-hoon-to|title=K-pop rocked by new scandal, fans ask FT Island's leader Choi Jong-hoon to quit|work=The Strait Times|date= March 13, 2019|accessdate=March 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, police booked Choi for illegally filming women without their consent, distributing a total of six videos, and bribery to cover up his drunk-driving incident.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/seungri-charged-over-embezzlement|title=Seungri charged over embezzlement|work=The Strait Times|date=April 2, 2019|accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.eonline.com/ap/news/1028847/choi-jong-hoon-is-booked-with-additional-charges-of-filming-illicit-videos|title=Choi Jong-Hoon Booked With Additional Charges of Filming Illicit Videos|work=E Online|date=April 1, 2019|accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref> On April 11, 2019, Choi admitted to spreading hidden camera photos taken without consent and also filming illegal hidden camera footage. He was charged with one count of sharing personally taken illegal footage and five counts of sharing footage from other sources.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2019/04/11/roy-kim-eddy-kim-choi-jong-hoon-admit-sharing-illegally-taken-photos|title=Roy Kim, Eddy Kim & Choi Jong Hoon admit to sharing illegally taken photos|work=SBS Australia|date=April 11, 2019|accessdate=April 11, 2019}}</ref> \n\n===Arrest===\nOn April 19, 2019, a woman came forward to [[SBS funE]], claiming that five men including Choi, had raped her after she was intoxicated in March 2016, and then shared the footage in a group chat. Choi denied the allegation, but admitted that he and the woman were together on that day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20190419000435|title=Jung Joon-young, Choi Jong-hoon accused of taking part in gang rape: report|work=[[The Korea Herald]]|first=Ju-young|last=Park|date=April 19, 2019|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5] '\uc9d1\ub2e8 \uc131\ud3ed\ud589 \uc758\ud639' \ucd5c\uc885\ud6c8 \ucd9c\uad6d\uae08\uc9c0...\ub0b4\uc8fc \uc18c\ud658|url=https://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=102&oid=052&aid=0001284958|date=April 25, 2019|work=[[YTN]]|accessdate=April 26, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> On May 10, 2019, Choi was arrested on the gang rape allegations and was indicted on charge of taking part in a gang rape in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Singer Choi Jong-hoon Arrested for Alleged Gang Rape|url=http://world.kbs.co.kr/service/news_view.htm?lang=e&Seq_Code=145075|date=May 10, 2019|work=[[KBS World]]|accessdate=May 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Boy Band Member Arrested for Rape|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2019/05/10/2019051001325.html|date=May 10, 2019|work=[[The Chosun Ilbo]]|first=Seung-jae|last=Kim|accessdate=May 10, 2019}}</ref> On November 29, 2019, Choi was sentenced to five years in prison.<ref>{{cite news|title=K-pop stars Jung Joon-young and Choi Jong-hoon sentenced for rape|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-50596943|website=[[BBC]]|date=November 29, 2019|accessdate=November 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=K-pop stars Jung Joon-young and Choi Jong-hoon sentenced to prison for rape|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-29/k-pop-stars-jung-joon-young-choi-jong-hoon-sentenced-prison-rape/11752066|website=[[ABC News]]|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television series===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 700px;\"\n! Year !! Network !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2008 || [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]] ||''[[On Air (TV series)|On Air]]'' || Himself || Cameo (Ep. 1)\n|-\n| 2009 || [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]] || ''[[Style (TV series)|Style]]'' || Himself || Cameo (Ep. 6)\n|-\n| 2012\u20132013 || [[tvN]] || ''Romantic & Idol Season 2'' || Himself || Cast member\n|-\n| 2013\u20132014 || [[TVN (South Korea)|tvN]] || ''[[Cheongdam-dong 111]]'' || Himself || Reality show\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2015 ||[[Naver| Naver TV cast]], [[KBS2]] || ''Prince's Prince'' || Park Shi-hyun  || Lead role, web drama\n|-\n| [[JTBC]] || ''Heroes'' || Choi Hee-yeol || Lead role\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2017 || [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]] || ''Law of the Jungle'' || Himself || Sumatra Guest (Ep. 261 - 264)\n|-\n|Naver TV Cast || ''Unexpected Heroes'' || Min Su-ho || Web-drama\n|-\n|2018 || [[Maeil Broadcasting Network|MBN]] || ''[[Real Life Men and Women]]'' || Himself || Cast member\n|}\n\n===Film===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 700px;\"\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[You're My Pet (film)|You're My Pet]]'' || Ji Eun-soo || Supporting role\n|}\n\n==Discography==\n{{See also|F.T. Island discography}}\n\n===Guest appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20em;\"|Title\n! scope=\"col\"|Year\n! scope=\"col\"|Release\n! scope=\"col\"|{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|\"Wish Ver.2\" ({{Korean|hangul=\uc18c\ub9dd Ver.2|rr=Somang Ver.2|labels=no}})\n| 2009\n| ''Errand''\n| \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Choi Jong-hoon}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n \n{{F.T. Island}}\n{{Mnet Media}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Choi, Jong-hoon}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:FNC Entertainment artists]