_id=1002576393 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061208201731/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002576393 |title=05/06 series |date=May 26, 2006 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |archivedate=December 8, 2006 |accessdate=January 30, 2010}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | 2.5/6<ref name=\"THR-20060526\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center; background-color:#F9F9F9\" | '''#86'''<ref name=\"THR-20060526\"/>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Teachers (UK TV series)]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0494188|Teachers}}\n* {{tv.com show|teachers|Teachers}}\n{{Teachers (TV series)}}\n\n[[Category:2000s American high school television series]]\n[[Category:2000s American sitcoms]]\n[[Category:2006 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2006 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American television series based on British television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by Universal Television]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in New Jersey]]\n", "name_user": "174.250.144.242", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Teachers_(2006_TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "WRNB", "text_new": "{{short description|Urban adult contemporary radio station in Philadelphia}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| name               = WRNB\n| image              = \n| city               = [[Media, Pennsylvania]]\n| area               = [[Delaware Valley|Greater Philadelphia (Delaware Valley)]]\n| branding           = ''100.3 WRNB''\n| slogan             = '''Philly's R&B Station'''\n| frequency          = 100.3 [[Hertz|MHz]] {{HD Radio}}\n| translator         =\n| repeater           =\n| airdate            = November 8, [[1982 in radio|1982]] (as WKSZ)\n| format             = FM/HD1: [[Urban adult contemporary]]<br>HD2: [[Urban contemporary]] ([[WPHI-FM|Hip Hop 103.9]] simulcast)\n| language           = [[English language|English]]\n| erp                = 17,000 [[watt]]s (analog)<br>650 [[watt]]s (digital)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/prefill_and_display.pl?Application_id=1416340&Service=FD&Form_id=335&Facility_id=25079 |title=FCC 335-FM Digital Notification [WRNB] |date=February 18, 2011 |website=fcc.gov |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |access-date=2018-05-10}}</ref>\n| haat               = {{convert|259|m|ft|sp=us}}\n| class              = B\n| facility_id        = 25079\n| coordinates        = {{coord|40|02|36|N|75|14|33|W|region:US-PA_type:landmark}} ([[North American Datum#North American Datum of 1927|NAD27]])\n| callsign_meaning   = '''W R'''hythm a'''N'''d '''B'''lues\n| former_callsigns   = WKSZ (1982\u20131993)<br>WPLY (1993\u20132005)<br>WPHI (2005\u20132011)\n| former_frequencies = \n| affiliations       =\n| owner              = [[Urban One]]\n| licensee           = Radio One Licenses, LLC\n| sister_stations    = [[WPHI-FM]], [[WPPZ-FM]]\n| webcast            = [http://rnbphilly.com/listen-live/ Listen Live]\n| website            = [http://rnbphilly.com/ rnbphilly.com]\n}}\n\n'''WRNB''' (100.3 [[FM broadcasting|FM]], \"100.3 WRNB\") is a [[commercial radio|commercial]] [[FM radio|FM]] [[radio station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to serve [[Media, Pennsylvania]] in the [[Philadelphia]]/[[Delaware Valley]] [[media market|radio market]]. It is owned by [[Radio One (Company)|Radio One]] and airs an [[urban adult contemporary]] [[radio format]]. In afternoon [[drive time]], WRNB carries the [[radio syndication|syndicated]] [[D. L. Hughley]] Show.\n\nWRNB's studios and offices are located in [[Bala Cynwyd, Pennsylvania|Bala Cynwyd]], with the transmitter located in the Roxborough neighborhood of [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]] at ({{coord|40|02|36.0|N|75|14|32.0|W}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://transition.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/fmq?call=WRNB |title=FM Query Results for WRNB |website=fcc.gov |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |accessdate=2018-05-10}}</ref> The station is short-spaced with two other co-channel FM stations (see [[WRNB#Signal note|See &sect; Signal note]] below).\n\n==History==\n===Early Years===\nIn the 1940s, 100.3 FM first went on the air in Philadelphia as '''KYW-FM''', the [[sister station]] to [[KYW (AM)|KYW]]. KYW-FM later moved to 92.5 MHz. In 1962, '''WXUR-FM''' [[sign-on|signed on]], licensed to the suburban community of Media.<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1968/B%202%20Broadcasting%20Yearbook%201968.pdf Broadcasting Yearbook 1968 page B-140]</ref> It was powered at only 4,200 watts, [[simulcast]]ing the [[Christian radio|Christian programming]] of its sister station WXUR (now [[WPHE]] in [[Phoenixville, Pennsylvania]]). WXUR-AM-FM were owned by [[Carl McIntire]], a [[Bible Presbyterian Church|Bible Presbyterian]] minister. In 1973, the [[Federal Communications Commission]] revoked the licenses for both stations, with the FCC ruling that WXUR-AM-FM violated the [[Fairness Doctrine]], refusing to air competing viewpoints. The 100.3 frequency then went [[Dark (broadcasting)|dark]] for eight years. \n\n===WKSZ Kiss 100===\nIn 1981, after a seven-year comparative hearing, the FCC awarded the license to the Greater Media Radio Company, owned by Daniel Lerner. The name referred to the station's city of license, Media, and was not associated with the larger [[Greater Media]], Inc., which locally owned [[WMGK]], [[WKDN (AM)|WPEN]] and other stations around the U.S. On November 8, 1982, 100.3 FM returned to the air, this time as '''WKSZ''', \"Kiss 100,\" with a [[soft adult contemporary]] format.<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1983/B-Radio-Neb-Terr-1983-YB.pdf Broadcasting Yearbook 1983 page B-208]</ref> By 1987, Kiss 100 was the #1 Arbitron-ranked station among women ages 25 to 54. \n\nIn the early 1990s, however, the battle for AC listeners heated up, with WEAZ (now [[WBEB]]) becoming the dominant station for soft music in Philadelphia. Kiss 100 lost ground in the ratings, falling to 17th place in 1992. WKSZ tried to combine AC and [[oldies]] with what the station called the \"50/50 Mix.\" This failed to turn ratings around, and in 1993, Kiss 100 returned to a [[playlist]] of AC love songs.\n\n===WPLY as Y100===\nOn March 15, 1993, at 6 a.m., with the station still struggling, WKSZ became \"Z100,\" flipping to a [[contemporary hit radio|Top 40]] format. The flip came three days after [[WISX|Eagle 106]] gave up Top 40 and switched to [[smooth jazz]], creating an opening which WKSZ hoped to fill. New York's [[WHTZ]], located on the same frequency of 100.3 MHz, and calling itself \"Z100\" since 1983, demanded that WKSZ drop the name to avoid listener confusion. After a brief legal battle, the call letters and name were changed to '''WPLY''', \"Y100.\" The station initially had a slight [[alternative rock]] lean, but still played other Top 40 hits, including pop and dance. By early 1995, WPLY evolved into a full time [[modern rock]] format, which lasted nearly ten years.<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1996/B-NE-Ter-BC-YB-1996.pdf Broadcasting & Cable Yearbook 1996 page B-359]</ref> Through the late 1990s, Y100 leaned towards [[Modern AC]], and would shift towards an [[active rock]] lean in 2000. \n\nIn 2000, the station was bought by [[Radio One (Company)|Radio One]] for $80 million.<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/2001/D-Radio-NE-TER-BC-YB-2001.pdf Broadcasting & Cable Yearbook page D-385]</ref> Radio One focuses mostly on urban music and didn't plan to program an alternative rock station. The company tried to make a deal to swap formats with [[Greater Media]]'s WEJM (now [[WBEN-FM]]), which, at the time, ran a [[rhythmic oldies]] format called \"Jammin Gold,\" which would have better fit into Radio One's portfolio. The deal fell through, and Radio One continued to run Y100 as a modern rock station for nearly five years. While ratings had gone down, the station still was moderately successful.\n\n===Switch with 103.9===\nOn February 24, [[2005 in radio|2005]], at 11:50 p.m., Y100 ended its alternative rock format. '''WPHI''', an [[urban contemporary]] station at 103.9 MHz, also owned by Radio One and known as \"103.9 The Beat,\" moved to 100.3 FM. The station at 103.9, in turn, flipped to [[urban gospel]] as [[WPHI|WPPZ-FM]], \"Praise 103.9.\" The last song on \"Y100\" was \"[[Alive (Pearl Jam song)|Alive]]\" by [[Pearl Jam]] (which was also the first and last song on [[WPPZ|WDRE]]).<ref>https://mycitypaper.com/articles/2005-03-31/cover.shtml</ref><ref>[http://formatchange.com/y100-announces-format-change/ Y100 Announces Format Change]</ref><ref>[http://formatchange.com/y100-1003-wply-signs-off/ Y100 Signs Off]</ref> By [[2006 in radio|2006]], [[Nielsen BDS]]/[[Radio & Records]] moved WPHI to the [[urban contemporary]] panel. [[Mediabase]] followed suit in [[2011 in radio|2011]]. WPHI-FM's chief rival was [[WUSL]], which had been Philadelphia's long-time Urban Contemporary leader.\n\nIn fall 2005, former rival personality Colby Colb was hired as the Program Director and afternoon host. For the next few years, 100.3 The Beat enjoyed high ratings, helped by Miss Jones in the morning and Colby Colb in the afternoon. Monie Love and Pooch took over mornings in 2005, with other [[disc jockey]]s on the station including Micheal Shawn, DJ Touchtone, DJ Jay Ski, Megatron, DJ Bent Rock, Moshay, Toshamakia, DJ JDS, Laiya and Hansoul. In late 2010, WPHI-FM became the Philadelphia home of the Star and Buc Wild Morning Show, [[radio syndication|syndicated]] from [[New York City]]. The show had actually been heard in Philadelphia in early 2006 on WUSL but had drawn some controversy and was dropped. \n\n===Switch with 107.9===\n[[File:100.3 WRNB.png|thumb|175px|Logo as \"100.3 WRNB\" from 2011-2013]]\nOn August 27, [[2011 in radio|2011]], WPHI dropped the \"Beat\" moniker for \"100.3 Philly.\" Radio One was preparing to make another frequency switch, this time moving 107.9 '''WRNB''' to 100.3 MHz on September 1st.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/53262/107-9-wrnb-philadelphia-to-move-to-100-3-on-september-1/ 107.9 WRNB to Move to 100.3 on September 1]</ref><ref>[http://formatchange.com/100-3-the-beat-becomes-wrnb/ 100.3 The Beat Becomes WRNB]</ref> WRNB was simulcast on both 100.3 and 107.9 until September 2nd, when the WPHI call letters moved to 107.9, adopted the former \"Beat\" format and rebranded as \"Hot 107.9.\" (WRNB would continue to air an Urban AC format after the move.)\n\n===Urban Oldies===\n[[File:Oldschool1003.png|thumb|Logo as \"Old School 100.3\" from 2013-2016]]\nOn March 29, 2013, WRNB went jockless and began promoting a \"big announcement\" at 5 p.m. on April 1st. At that time, after playing \"[[Keep Your Head to the Sky]]\" by [[Earth, Wind, & Fire]], WRNB flipped to [[urban oldies]] as \"Old School 100.3.\" The first song on \"Old School\" was \"[[Atomic Dog]]\" by [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/81395/wrnb-philadelphia-going-old-school/ WRNB Going Old School]</ref><ref>[http://formatchange.com/wrnb-goes-old-school/ WRNB Flips to Old School]</ref> \n\nThe format played [[Motown]], [[disco]], [[funk]], [[new jack swing]], [[freestyle music|freestyle]], and early [[hip hop]] from the 1960s to the early 2000s. The new format was designed to better compete with the dominant Urban AC station in Philadelphia, [[WDAS-FM]].\n\nIn November 2014, sister station [[WPHI-FM|WPHI]] moved to a [[classic hip-hop]] format. In response, WRNB re-added some current music, although the station continued to focus on older urban hits.\n\n===Return to Urban AC===\nOn October 6, 2016, WRNB moved back to [[urban adult contemporary]] music, once more calling itself \"100.3 WRNB,\" and dropping the \"Old School\" reference.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/108592/wrnb-drops-old-school-100-3-branding/ WRNB Drops Old School 100.3 Branding] Radioinsight - October 6, 2016</ref>\n[[File:WRNB.png|thumb|Logo as \"100.3 WRNB\" from 2016-2020]]\n\n===History of WRNB Call Letters===\nBeginning in the 1950s, the call sign WRNB was licensed to [[North Carolina]]'s first full-time [[rock 'n roll]] radio station, a 1000-watt outlet in [[New Bern, North Carolina|New Bern]] located at [[AM 1490]] (now [[sports radio]] [[WWNB]]). WRNB 1490 was also famous for being one of the first radio stations to play [[Carolina Beach Music]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n\n==Signal note==\nWRNB is short-spaced to two other co-channel Class B stations: [[WHTZ]] ''Z100'' (licensed to serve [[Newark, New Jersey]]) and [[WBIG-FM]] ''Big 100'' (licensed to serve [[Washington, D.C.]]). The cities WRNB and WHTZ are licensed to serve are only 86 miles apart,<ref>{{cite web|title=How Far is it Between Media, PA, USA and Newark, NJ, USA |url=https://www.freemaptools.com/how-far-is-it-between-media_-pa,-usa-and-newark_-nj,-usa.htm |website=Free Map Tools |accessdate=2018-05-10}}</ref> while the cities WRNB and WBIG-FM are licensed to serve are only 112 miles apart.<ref>{{cite web|title=How Far is it Between Media, PA, USA and Washington, DC, USA |url=https://www.freemaptools.com/how-far-is-it-between-media_-pa,-usa-and-washington_-dc,-usa.htm |website=Free Map Tools |accessdate=2018-05-10}}</ref> The minimum distance between two Class B stations operating on the same channel according to current [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]] rules is 150 miles.<ref name=\"FCC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CFR-2012-title47-vol4/pdf/CFR-2012-title47-vol4-sec73-207.pdf |title=Minimum distance separation between stations. 47 CFR \u00a7 73.207 (1) |accessdate=2018-05-10}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://wrnbphilly.com/ Official website of 100.3 WRNB]\n*{{FM station data|WRNB}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061017031153/http://www.1003thebeatphilly.com/home.asp Official website 100.3 The Beat] (2006 archive)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050205194953/http://y100.com/home.asp Official website of Y100] (2005 archive)\n\n{{Philadelphia Radio}}\n{{Urban Radio Stations in Pennsylvania}}\n{{Radio One}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Philadelphia|RNB]]\n[[Category:Urban One stations]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Urban adult contemporary radio station in Philadelphia}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| name               = WRNB\n| image              = \n| city               = [[Media, Pennsylvania]]\n| area               = [[Delaware Valley|Greater Philadelphia (Delaware Valley)]]\n| branding           = ''100.3 WRNB''\n| slogan             = '''Philly's R&B Station'''\n| frequency          = 100.3 [[Hertz|MHz]] {{HD Radio}}\n| translator         =\n| repeater           =\n| airdate            = November 8, [[1982 in radio|1982]] (as WKSZ)\n| format             = FM/HD1: [[Urban adult contemporary|Urban AC]]<br>HD2: [[Urban Contemporary]] ([[WPHI-FM|Hip Hop 103.9]] simulcast)\n| language           = [[English language|English]]\n| erp                = 17,000 [[watt]]s (analog)<br>650 [[watt]]s (digital)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/prefill_and_display.pl?Application_id=1416340&Service=FD&Form_id=335&Facility_id=25079 |title=FCC 335-FM Digital Notification [WRNB] |date=February 18, 2011 |website=fcc.gov |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |access-date=2018-05-10}}</ref>\n| haat               = {{convert|259|m|ft|sp=us}}\n| class              = B\n| facility_id        = 25079\n| coordinates        = {{coord|40|02|36|N|75|14|33|W|region:US-PA_type:landmark}} ([[North American Datum#North American Datum of 1927|NAD27]])\n| callsign_meaning   = '''W R'''hythm a'''N'''d '''B'''lues\n| former_callsigns   = WKSZ (1982-1993)<br>WPLY (1993-2005)<br>WPHI (2005-2011)\n| former_frequencies = \n| affiliations       =\n| owner              = [[Urban One]]\n| licensee           = Radio One Licenses, LLC\n| sister_stations    = [[WPHI-FM]], [[WPPZ-FM]]\n| webcast            = [http://rnbphilly.com/listen-live/ Listen Live]\n| website            = [http://rnbphilly.com/ rnbphilly.com]\n}}\n\n'''WRNB''' (100.3 [[FM broadcasting|FM]], \"100.3 WRNB\") is a [[commercial radio|commercial]] [[FM radio|FM]] [[radio station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to serve [[Media, Pennsylvania]] in the [[Philadelphia]]/[[Delaware Valley]] [[media market|radio market]]. It is owned by [[Radio One (Company)|Radio One]] and airs an [[urban adult contemporary]] [[radio format]]. In afternoon [[drive time]], WRNB carries the [[radio syndication|syndicated]] [[D. L. Hughley]] Show.\n\nWRNB's studios and offices are located in [[Bala Cynwyd, Pennsylvania|Bala Cynwyd]], with the transmitter located in the Roxborough neighborhood of [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]] at ({{coord|40|02|36.0|N|75|14|32.0|W}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://transition.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/fmq?call=WRNB |title=FM Query Results for WRNB |website=fcc.gov |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |accessdate=2018-05-10}}</ref> The station is short-spaced with two other co-channel FM stations (see [[WRNB#Signal note|See &sect; Signal note]] below).\n\n==History==\n===Early Years===\nIn the 1940s, 100.3 FM first went on the air in Philadelphia as '''KYW-FM''', the [[sister station]] to [[KYW (AM)|KYW]]. KYW-FM later moved to 92.5 MHz. In 1962, '''WXUR-FM''' [[sign-on|signed on]], licensed to the suburban community of Media.<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1968/B%202%20Broadcasting%20Yearbook%201968.pdf Broadcasting Yearbook 1968 page B-140]</ref> It was powered at only 4,200 watts, [[simulcast]]ing the [[Christian radio|Christian programming]] of its sister station WXUR (now [[WPHE]] in [[Phoenixville, Pennsylvania]]). WXUR-AM-FM were owned by [[Carl McIntire]], a [[Bible Presbyterian Church|Bible Presbyterian]] minister. In 1973, the [[Federal Communications Commission]] revoked the licenses for both stations, with the FCC ruling that WXUR-AM-FM violated the [[Fairness Doctrine]], refusing to air competing viewpoints. The 100.3 frequency then went [[Dark (broadcasting)|dark]] for eight years. \n\n===WKSZ Kiss 100===\nIn 1981, after a seven-year comparative hearing, the FCC awarded the license to the Greater Media Radio Company, owned by Daniel Lerner. The name referred to the station's city of license, Media, and was not associated with the larger [[Greater Media]], Inc., which locally owned [[WMGK]], [[WKDN (AM)|WPEN]] and other stations around the U.S. On November 8, 1982, 100.3 FM returned to the air, this time as '''WKSZ''', \"Kiss 100,\" with a [[soft adult contemporary]] format.<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1983/B-Radio-Neb-Terr-1983-YB.pdf Broadcasting Yearbook 1983 page B-208]</ref> By 1987, Kiss 100 was the #1 Arbitron-ranked station among women ages 25 to 54. \n\nIn the early 1990s, however, the battle for AC listeners heated up, with WEAZ (now [[WBEB]]) becoming the dominant station for soft music in Philadelphia. Kiss 100 lost ground in the ratings, falling to 17th place in 1992. WKSZ tried to combine AC and [[oldies]] with what the station called the \"50/50 Mix.\" This failed to turn ratings around, and in 1993, Kiss 100 returned to a [[playlist]] of AC love songs.\n\n===WPLY as Y100===\nOn March 15, 1993, at 6 a.m., with the station still struggling, WKSZ became \"Z100,\" flipping to a [[contemporary hit radio|Top 40]] format. The flip came three days after [[WISX|Eagle 106]] gave up Top 40 and switched to [[smooth jazz]], creating an opening which WKSZ hoped to fill. New York's [[WHTZ]], located on the same frequency of 100.3 MHz, and calling itself \"Z100\" since 1983, demanded that WKSZ drop the name to avoid listener confusion. After a brief legal battle, the call letters and name were changed to '''WPLY''', \"Y100.\" The station initially had a slight [[alternative rock]] lean, but still played other Top 40 hits, including pop and dance. By early 1995, WPLY evolved into a full time [[modern rock]] format, which lasted nearly ten years.<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1996/B-NE-Ter-BC-YB-1996.pdf Broadcasting & Cable Yearbook 1996 page B-359]</ref> Through the late 1990s, Y100 leaned towards [[Modern AC]], and would shift towards an [[active rock]] lean in 2000. \n\nIn 2000, the station was bought by [[Radio One (Company)|Radio One]] for $80 million.<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/2001/D-Radio-NE-TER-BC-YB-2001.pdf Broadcasting & Cable Yearbook page D-385]</ref> Radio One focuses mostly on urban music and didn't plan to program an alternative rock station. The company tried to make a deal to swap formats with [[Greater Media]]'s WEJM (now [[WBEN-FM]]), which, at the time, ran a [[rhythmic oldies]] format called \"Jammin Gold,\" which would have better fit into Radio One's portfolio. The deal fell through, and Radio One continued to run Y100 as a modern rock station for nearly five years. While ratings had gone down, the station still was moderately successful.\n\n===Switch with 103.9===\nOn February 24, [[2005 in radio|2005]], at 11:50 p.m., Y100 ended its alternative rock format. '''WPHI''', an [[urban contemporary]] station at 103.9 MHz, also owned by Radio One and known as \"103.9 The Beat,\" moved to 100.3 FM. The station at 103.9, in turn, flipped to [[urban gospel]] as [[WPHI|WPPZ-FM]], \"Praise 103.9.\" The last song on \"Y100\" was \"[[Alive (Pearl Jam song)|Alive]]\" by [[Pearl Jam]] (which was also the first and last song on [[WPPZ|WDRE]]).<ref>https://mycitypaper.com/articles/2005-03-31/cover.shtml</ref><ref>[http://formatchange.com/y100-announces-format-change/ Y100 Announces Format Change]</ref><ref>[http://formatchange.com/y100-1003-wply-signs-off/ Y100 Signs Off]</ref> By [[2006 in radio|2006]], [[Nielsen BDS]]/[[Radio & Records]] moved WPHI to the [[urban contemporary]] panel. [[Mediabase]] followed suit in [[2011 in radio|2011]]. WPHI-FM's chief rival was [[WUSL]], which had been Philadelphia's long-time Urban Contemporary leader.\n\nIn fall 2005, former rival personality Colby Colb was hired as the Program Director and afternoon host. For the next few years, 100.3 The Beat enjoyed high ratings, helped by Miss Jones in the morning and Colby Colb in the afternoon. Monie Love and Pooch took over mornings in 2005, with other [[disc jockey]]s on the station including Micheal Shawn, DJ Touchtone, DJ Jay Ski, Megatron, DJ Bent Rock, Moshay, Toshamakia, DJ JDS, Laiya and Hansoul. In late 2010, WPHI-FM became the Philadelphia home of the Star and Buc Wild Morning Show, [[radio syndication|syndicated]] from [[New York City]]. The show had actually been heard in Philadelphia in early 2006 on WUSL but had drawn some controversy and was dropped. \n\n===Switch with 107.9===\n[[File:100.3 WRNB.png|thumb|175px|Logo as \"100.3 WRNB\" from 2011-2013]]\nOn August 27, [[2011 in radio|2011]], WPHI dropped the \"Beat\" moniker for \"100.3 Philly.\" Radio One was preparing to make another frequency switch, this time moving 107.9 '''WRNB''' to 100.3 MHz on September 1st.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/53262/107-9-wrnb-philadelphia-to-move-to-100-3-on-september-1/ 107.9 WRNB to Move to 100.3 on September 1]</ref><ref>[http://formatchange.com/100-3-the-beat-becomes-wrnb/ 100.3 The Beat Becomes WRNB]</ref> WRNB was simulcast on both 100.3 and 107.9 until September 2nd, when the WPHI call letters moved to 107.9, adopted the former \"Beat\" format and rebranded as \"Hot 107.9.\" (WRNB would continue to air an Urban AC format after the move.)\n\n===Urban Oldies===\n[[File:Oldschool1003.png|thumb|Logo as \"Old School 100.3\" from 2013-2016]]\nOn March 29, 2013, WRNB went jockless and began promoting a \"big announcement\" at 5 p.m. on April 1st. At that time, after playing \"[[Keep Your Head to the Sky]]\" by [[Earth, Wind, & Fire]], WRNB flipped to [[urban oldies]] as \"Old School 100.3.\" The first song on \"Old School\" was \"[[Atomic Dog]]\" by [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]].<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/netgnomes/81395/wrnb-philadelphia-going-old-school/ WRNB Going Old School]</ref><ref>[http://formatchange.com/wrnb-goes-old-school/ WRNB Flips to Old School]</ref> \n\nThe format played [[Motown]], [[disco]], [[funk]], [[new jack swing]], [[freestyle music|freestyle]], and early [[hip hop]] from the 1960s to the early 2000s. The new format was designed to better compete with the dominant Urban AC station in Philadelphia, [[WDAS-FM]].\n\nIn November 2014, sister station [[WPHI-FM|WPHI]] moved to a [[classic hip-hop]] format. In response, WRNB re-added some current music, although the station continued to focus on older urban hits.\n\n===Return to Urban AC===\nOn October 6, 2016, WRNB moved back to [[urban adult contemporary]] music, once more calling itself \"100.3 WRNB,\" and dropping the \"Old School\" reference.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/108592/wrnb-drops-old-school-100-3-branding/ WRNB Drops Old School 100.3 Branding] Radioinsight - October 6, 2016</ref>\n[[File:WRNB.png|thumb|Logo as \"100.3 WRNB\" from 2016-2020]]\n\n===History of WRNB Call Letters===\nBeginning in the 1950s, the call sign WRNB was licensed to [[North Carolina]]'s first full-time [[rock 'n roll]] radio station, a 1000-watt outlet in [[New Bern, North Carolina|New Bern]] located at [[AM 1490]] (now [[sports radio]] [[WWNB]]). WRNB 1490 was also famous for being one of the first radio stations to play [[Carolina Beach Music]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n\n==Signal note==\nWRNB is short-spaced to two other co-channel Class B stations: [[WHTZ]] ''Z100'' (licensed to serve [[Newark, New Jersey]]) and [[WBIG-FM]] ''Big 100'' (licensed to serve [[Washington, D.C.]]). The cities WRNB and WHTZ are licensed to serve are only 86 miles apart,<ref>{{cite web|title=How Far is it Between Media, PA, USA and Newark, NJ, USA |url=https://www.freemaptools.com/how-far-is-it-between-media_-pa,-usa-and-newark_-nj,-usa.htm |website=Free Map Tools |accessdate=2018-05-10}}</ref> while the cities WRNB and WBIG-FM are licensed to serve are only 112 miles apart.<ref>{{cite web|title=How Far is it Between Media, PA, USA and Washington, DC, USA |url=https://www.freemaptools.com/how-far-is-it-between-media_-pa,-usa-and-washington_-dc,-usa.htm |website=Free Map Tools |accessdate=2018-05-10}}</ref> The minimum distance between two Class B stations operating on the same channel according to current [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]] rules is 150 miles.<ref name=\"FCC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CFR-2012-title47-vol4/pdf/CFR-2012-title47-vol4-sec73-207.pdf |title=Minimum distance separation between stations. 47 CFR \u00a7 73.207 (1) |accessdate=2018-05-10}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://wrnbphilly.com/ Official website of 100.3 WRNB]\n*{{FM station data|WRNB}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061017031153/http://www.1003thebeatphilly.com/home.asp Official website 100.3 The Beat] (2006 archive)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050205194953/http://y100.com/home.asp Official website of Y100] (2005 archive)\n\n{{Philadelphia Radio}}\n{{Urban Radio Stations in Pennsylvania}}\n{{Radio One}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Philadelphia|RNB]]\n[[Category:Urban One stations]]\n", "name_user": "Wcquidditch", "label": "safe", "comment": "per the Manual of Style,genres and radio formatsare not capitalized; etc.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WRNB"}
